xpr:(9+103.5+209.2+183.1+179.5)/(2+23+43+37+36)round2}}\n|}\n\nDeliveries dropped in 2018 because of a combination of the transition to the HondaJet Elite, timing of fleet deliveries and customers' schedules.<ref name=\"2018 Most delivery\">{{cite news |last1=Bollinger |first1=Luke |title=Honda Aircraft Co. delivered 37 jets in 2018, most among its category |url=https://www.bizjournals.com/triad/news/2019/02/21/honda-aircraft-co-delivered-37-jets-in-2018-most.html |accessdate=24 January 2020 |work=www.bizjournals.com |date=21 February 2019}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Aircontent\n|related=\n* [[Honda MH02]]\n|similar aircraft=\n* [[Cessna Citation M2]]<ref name=fg2015-03-27/>\n*[[Eclipse 550]]<ref name=cM2>\"[http://www.flyingmag.com/aircraft/jets/cessna-citation-m2-versus-world-comparison-specs Cessna Citation M2 Versus the World: Comparison Specs]\" ''Flying'', 11 November 2013.</ref>\n* [[Embraer Phenom 100]]\n|lists=\n* [[List of very light jets]]\n|see also=\n}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons|Honda HondaJet}}\n* {{Official website|http://www.hondajet.com/}}\n* {{cite web |url= http://www.hondajet.com/hondajet/specifications/ |title= HondaJet Specifications |publisher= Honda }}\n* {{cite web |url= http://world.honda.com/HondaJet/ |title= Hondajet |publisher= Honda worldwide}}\n* {{cite journal |url= http://icas.org/ICAS_ARCHIVE/ICAS2004/PAPERS/582.PDF |title= Development of the HondaJet |author= Michimasa Fujino, Honda R&D Americas |publisher= [[International Council of the Aeronautical Sciences]] |date= 2004}}\n\n{{Honda aircraft and aeroengines}}\n\n[[Category:Honda aircraft|HA-420]]\n[[Category:2000s Japanese business aircraft]]\n[[Category:2000s United States business aircraft]]\n[[Category:Very light jets]]\n[[Category:Twinjets]]\n[[Category:Engine-over-wing aircraft]]\n[[Category:T-tail aircraft]]\n[[Category:Aircraft first flown in 2003]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Very light business jet}}\n{|{{Infobox aircraft begin\n| name = HA-420 HondaJet\n| image = File:HondaJet Ryabtsev.jpg\n| caption = \n}}{{Infobox aircraft type\n| type = [[Business jet]]<br>[[Very light jet]]\n| manufacturer = [[Honda Aircraft Company]]<ref>[[Aviation Week & Space Technology]], ''First Flight for Production HondaJet'', 7 July 2014, p. 11</ref><br>\n| first flight = December 3, 2003\n| production = 2012\n| introduced = \n| retired = \n| national origin = [[Japan]]<br>[[United States]]\n| status = In production\n| produced = December 2015\u2013present\n| number built = 130 (Aug 2019)<ref name=Honda-PressRelease20190805>{{cite press release|url=https://www.hondajet.com/news/article?articleType=pressrelease&categoryType=bb18852e-25ce-443e-bbb9-24e2a59597a6 |title= The HondaJet Elite Obtains Chinese Type Certification |date=August 5, 2019|publisher=Honda Aircraft Company}}</ref>\n| program cost = roughly $1 billion (estimated)<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.reuters.com/article/us-honda-jet-idUSKBN16Y0CD |date= Mar 27, 2017 |title= Honda faces long haul to recoup jet costs |authors= Naomi Tajitsu, Maki Shiraki |agency= Reuters}}</ref>\n| unit cost = [[US$]]5.28 million (Elite, 2019)<ref name=BCA-2019>{{cite magazine |url= https://aviationweek.com/site-files/aviationweek.com/files/datasheets/gated/BCA_201906.pdf |title= Purchase Planning Handbook |magazine= Business & Commercial Aviation |date= June 2019 |publisher= Aviation Week Network |url-access= subscription}}</ref>\n| variants with their own articles = \n}}\n|}\n\nThe '''Honda HA-420 HondaJet''' is the first aircraft developed by the [[Honda Aircraft Company]]. It is a twin-engine, seven-seat [[light business jet]], and is also considered as a [[very light jet]].<ref name=\"HondaJet_Elite_Brochure\" /> It was designed in Japan in the late 1990s then developed and manufactured in [[Greensboro, North Carolina]], United States.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.news-record.com/business/local_business/greensboro-made-hondajet-debuts-at-wisconsin-airshow/article_95c1b6c4-16c2-11e4-80e1-0017a43b2370.html | title=Greensboro-made HondaJet debuts at Wisconsin airshow | date=July 28, 2014 |newspaper=News & Record | accessdate=20 March 2015 }}</ref> Its first flight took place in 2003 and deliveries commenced in December 2015.\n\n==Development==\n\nHonda began to study small sized [[business jet]]s in the late 1980s, using engines from other manufacturers. The Honda SHM-1/MH01 turboprop tested laminar flow wings,<ref name=opdo/> and the [[Honda MH02]] was fabricated and assembled at [[Mississippi State University#Accolades|Mississippi State University's Raspet Flight Research Laboratory]] in the late 1980s and early 1990s. The MH02 was a prototype using carbon fiber/epoxy composite materials and was the first all-composite light business jet to fly.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ae.msstate.edu/rfrl/pages/hondajet.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20030907012515/http://www.ae.msstate.edu/rfrl/pages/hondajet.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=2003-09-07 |title=Raspet Flight Research Laboratory: History/Honda Jet |publisher=Ae.msstate.edu |accessdate=2010-12-23 }}</ref> Flight testing on the MH02 continued through 1996, after which the aircraft was shipped to Japan.\n\nDesigner and company founder [[Michimasa Fujino]] sketched the HondaJet in 1997, and the concept was locked in 1999. Testing in the [[Boeing]] windtunnel indicated a valid concept in 1999.<ref name=opdo>Warwick, Graham. \"[http://www.hondajet.com/Content/pdf/FlightInternational_CoverStory.pdf Opening doors]\" ''[[Flight International]]'', 9\u201315 January 2007.</ref><ref name=fujTech/>\n\nA proof-of-concept (but not production-ready) version of the HondaJet first flew on December 3, 2003, at [[Piedmont Triad International Airport]] in [[Greensboro, North Carolina]].<ref>[http://www.wingsmagazine.com/content/view/7055/38/ \u201cDriven to Succeed.\u201d] Wingsmagazine.com Retrieved February 5, 2015.</ref> Honda approved commercial development of the HondaJet in 2004.<ref>Matoon, Jeff. \"[http://www.hondajet.com/Content/pdf/PILOT_MAG_Reprint.pdf The world of HondaJet]\" page 5. ''PilotMag'', May/June 2012</ref> The HondaJet made its world debut on July 28, 2005, at the annual [[EAA AirVenture Oshkosh]] airshow.<ref>[http://www.ainonline.com/aviation-news/aviation-international-news/2006-10-04/hondajet-makes-world-debut-eaa-airventure \u201cHondaJet makes world debut at EAA AirVenture.\u201d] AINonline.com Retrieved 5 February 2015.</ref> At the following year's Airventure, Honda announced that it would commercialize the HondaJet.<ref>[http://www.ainonline.com/aviation-news/ainalerts/2006-11-14/honda-gives-green-light-hondajet \u201cHonda Gives Green Light for HondaJet.\u201d] AINonline.com (14 November 2006). Retrieved February 5, 2015.</ref>\n\nThe first [[Federal Aviation Administration|FAA]]-conforming (built to Federal Aviation Administration rules) HondaJet achieved its first flight on 20 December 2010.<ref>Welsh, Jonathan. [https://blogs.wsj.com/drivers-seat/2010/12/22/new-honda-jet-makes-first-flight/ \u201cNew HondaJet Makes First Flight.\u201d] Blogs.WSJ.com (22 December 2010).  Retrieved 5 February 2015/</ref> The first flight of the first production HondaJet occurred on June 27, 2014,<ref>Lavender, Chris. [http://www.aviationpros.com/news/11543371/flight-sends-hondajet-into-next-phase  Flight sends Hondajet into next phase] Times-News, Burlington, N.C. July 2014</ref><ref name=\"AW&ST, 7 July 2014, p. 11\">AW&ST, 7 July 2014, p. 11</ref><ref>[http://www.fly-corporate.com/article/oem-brokerage/first-production-hondajet-takes \u201cFirst Production HondaJet Takes Off.\u201d] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402133436/http://www.fly-corporate.com/article/oem-brokerage/first-production-hondajet-takes |date=2015-04-02 }} Fly-Corporate.com Retrieved 27 January 2015.</ref> and it was displayed at that year's AirVenture on 28 July.<ref>[http://www.midwestflyer.com/?p=7943 \u201cFirst Production HondaJet Makes Public Debut At AirVenture.\u201d] MidwestFlyer.com Retrieved 27 January 2015.</ref><ref>Whitfield, Bethany. \"[http://www.flyingmag.com/aircraft/jets/production-conforming-hondajet-debuts-oshkosh Production Conforming HondaJet Debuts at Oshkosh]\" ''[[Flying (magazine)|Flying]]'', 29 July 2014.</ref><ref>Reynolds, Ric. \"[http://www.eaa.org/en/airventure/eaa-airventure-news-and-multimedia/eaa-airventure-news/eaa-airventure-oshkosh/2014-07-28-hondajet-makes-another-oshkosh-first HondaJet Makes Another Oshkosh First] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140730014158/http://www.eaa.org/en/airventure/eaa-airventure-news-and-multimedia/eaa-airventure-news/eaa-airventure-oshkosh/2014-07-28-hondajet-makes-another-oshkosh-first |date=2014-07-30 }}\" [[Experimental Aircraft Association]], 28 July 2014.</ref> Four HondaJets had test-flown 2,500 hours {{As of|2015||df=|lc=y}}.<ref name=avw2015-03-30>{{cite web |first=Elaine |last=Kauh |url=http://www.avweb.com/avwebflash/news/HondaJet-Nears-Final-Type-Certification-223749-1.html |title=HondaJet Nears Final Type Certification |work=avweb.com|agency=Aviation Publishing Group |date=27 March 2015 |accessdate=30 March 2015 }}</ref>\n\nAfter the commercialization of the HondaJet HA-420 was announced by Honda in 2006, the first delivery was planned for 2010.<ref>{{cite press release |url= https://www.hondajet.com/news/article?articleType=pressrelease&categoryType=e352e647-3a15-4373-abe8-4468869a6f34 |title= Honda Aircraft Company Established |date= August 6, 2006 |publisher= Honda Aircraft Company}}</ref> In Spring 2009, it was delayed by a year.<ref>{{Cite news |title= HondaJet delays delivery of first light jet; opening of Albany operation also delayed |url= http://www.bizjournals.com/albany/stories/2009/04/27/daily45.html |work= Albany Business Review |date= Apr 30, 2009}}</ref> In May 2010, the projected certification date was late 2012.<ref>{{Cite news |title= More Delays Logged in HondaJet Program |url= http://www.ainonline.com/aviation-news/aviation-international-news/2010-05-26/more-delays-logged-hondajet-program |work= Aviation International News |date= May 26, 2010}}</ref> The program was incrementally delayed several more times.<ref>{{Cite news |title = HondaJet Certification Pushed Out to Late 2014 |url= http://www.ainonline.com/aviation-news/business-aviation/2013-05-09/hondajet-certification-pushed-out-late-2014 |work= Aviation International News |date= May 9, 2013}}</ref>\n\nThe HondaJet was awarded a \"[[Airworthiness certificate#Special Airworthiness Certificate|Provisional Type Certificate]]\u201c from the [[FAA]] in March 2015.  This enabled continued production<ref name=\"ain2015-03-27\">{{cite news |first=Matt |last=Thurber |url=http://www.ainonline.com/aviation-news/business-aviation/2015-03-27/hondajet-receives-provisional-faa-certification |title=HondaJet Receives Provisional FAA Certification  |work=Aviation International News |date=27 March 2015 |accessdate=27 March 2015 }}</ref><ref name=\"fg2015-03-27\" /> and demonstration flights, including a HondaJet tour in Japan and Europe in 2015.<ref name=ain2015-05-18>{{cite news |first=Kerry |last=Lynch |url=http://www.ainonline.com/aviation-news/business-aviation/2015-05-18/hondajet-debuts-europe-certification-close |title=HondaJet Debuts In Europe With Certification Close |work=Aviation International News |date=18 May 2015 |accessdate=18 May 2015 }}</ref> The aircraft received its FAA [[type certificate]] in December 2015<ref>{{cite news |title= FAA awards type certification to HondaJet |date= December 9, 2015 |work= FlightGlobal |author= Stephen Trimble |url= https://www.flightglobal.com/news/articles/faa-awards-type-certification-to-hondajet-419890/}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= http://rgl.faa.gov/Regulatory_and_Guidance_Library/rgMakeModel.nsf/0/4d17265c4e1d151886257f37005117a4/$FILE/A00018AT_Rev0.pdf |title= TYPE CERTIFICATE DATA SHEET NO. A00018AT Revision 0 |date= December 8, 2015 |publisher= FAA}}</ref><ref>{{cite press release|url=https://www.hondajet.com/news/article?articleType=pressrelease&categoryType=d82b11b7-98a3-4a02-9688-5bd05eef476d|title=HondaJet Receives Type Certification From Federal Aviation Administration|date=December 9, 2015|publisher=HondaJet}}</ref> and received its [[European Aviation Safety Agency]] (EASA) type certificate in May 2016<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.flyingmag.com/hondajet-achieves-easa-certification |title=HondaJet Achieves EASA Certification|work=[[Flying (magazine)|Flying]] |accessdate=24 May 2016}}</ref> The HondaJet was also certified in [[Japan Civil Aviation Bureau|Japan]] in December 2018.<ref name=Honda-PressRelease20181210>{{cite press release|url=https://www.hondajet.com/news/article?articleType=pressrelease&categoryType=59e1bc16-4c1a-4380-9469-9694d373a9c6|title=HondaJet Elite Receives Type Certification in Japan|date=December 10, 2018|publisher=Honda Aircraft Company}}</ref>\n\n===Production===\n[[File:HondaJetFormation.jpg|right|thumb|HondaJet formation]]\n\nThe production aircraft are built at [[Piedmont Triad International Airport]]. Construction of the factory began in 2007 and was completed in late 2011.<ref name=\"awHJ\">Garvey, William. [http://www.aviationweek.com/aw/generic/story_generic.jsp?channel=awst&id=news/awst/2011/01/03/AW_01_03_2011_p32-279571.xml HondaJet flight testing is underway] ''[[Aviation Week]]''. Accessed: 9 January 2011.</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://hondajet.honda.com/news/article.aspx?ArticleType=pressrelease&CatType=news_detail_87.xml |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090511162330/http://hondajet.honda.com/news/article.aspx?ArticleType=pressrelease&CatType=news_detail_87.xml |url-status=dead |archive-date=2009-05-11 |title=Honda Aircraft Company Updates HondaJet Program &#124; HondaJet &#124; News |publisher=Hondajet.honda.com |date=2009-04-30 |accessdate=2010-12-23 }}</ref> In early 2015, there were 12 aircraft in final assembly and five more in earlier stages of production.<ref name=\"fg2015-03-27\" /> Twenty aircraft were in production by May 2015. Honda estimated it would produce 40 aircraft in the first full year and up to 60 each year after that.<ref name=\"ain2015-05-18\" /> The engine factory achieved certification in March 2015.<ref name=fg2015-03-27/><ref name=ain2015-03-18>{{cite news |first=Chad |last=Trautvetter |url=http://www.ainonline.com/aviation-news/business-aviation/2015-03-18/ge-honda-wins-faa-production-certificate-hf120-engine |title=GE Honda Wins FAA Production Certificate for HF120 Engine |work=Aviation International News |date=18 March 2015 |accessdate=21 March 2015 }}</ref>\n\nHonda delivered the first customer aircraft on December 23, 2015, at its world headquarters in Greensboro, North Carolina.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://myfox8.com/2015/12/24/honda-aircraft-delivers-its-first-hondajet/|title=Honda Aircraft delivers its first HondaJet|date=24 December 2015|work=[[WGHP|Fox 8]]}}</ref> The first delivery of a HondaJet to a European aircraft dealer took place in April 2016.<ref name=\"AOPA0716\">{{cite web|last1=Namowitz|first1=Dan|title=HONDA GAINS FAA PRODUCTION CERTIFICATE|url=https://www.aopa.org/news-and-media/all-news/2016/july/11/hondajet-gains-faa-production-certificate|website=AOPA |date=11 July 2016 |accessdate=18 July 2016}}</ref> About 20% of the approximately 100 aircraft on order are destined for European customers as reported in April 2016.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Haines|first1=Thomas|title=EUROPE GETS ITS FIRST HONDAJET (Apr 20, 2016)|url=https://www.aopa.org/news-and-media/all-news/2016/april/20/europe-gets-its-first-hondajet|website=AOPA.org|accessdate=21 September 2017}}</ref>\n\nHonda plans to ramp up production to 80 units per year after March 2019. Sixteen aircraft were delivered in the first three quarters of 2016, reaching a 36 per year production rate.<ref name=AIN161114>{{cite news |url= http://www.ainonline.com/aviation-news/business-aviation/2016-11-14/hondajet-production-reach-80-annually-march-2019 |title= HondaJet Production To Reach 80 Annually by March 2019 |author= Chad Trautvetter |date= November 14, 2016 |work= Aviation International News}}</ref> In 2017, 15 were produced in the first quarter, and the annual target is between 55 and 60 aircraft.<ref name=Flight22May2017>{{cite news |url= https://www.flightglobal.com/news/articles/ebace-hondajet-global-sales-drive-ramps-up-with-se-437438/ |title= HondaJet global sales drive ramps up with SE Asia entry |date= 22 May 2017 |author= Kerry Reals |work= Flight Global}}</ref> The HondaJet finished 2017 as the year's most-delivered very light jet,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.greensboro.com/gnr/hondajet-most-delivered-in-its-category-in/article_730c3c55-f5cf-517d-af8c-e27b1b0fbc7c.html|work=Greensboro News & Record |title= HondaJet 'most delivered' in its category in 2017|date= 21 Feb 2018}}</ref> and in 2018 was the second-most delivered VLJ, behind the [[Cirrus Vision SF50]].<ref name=GAMA2018>{{cite journal|url=https://gama.aero/wp-content/uploads/GAMA-2018-Annual-Report-FINAL.pdf|title=2018 Annual Report|author=General Aviation Manufacturers Association|date=2019|accessdate=24 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2019, Honda Aircraft announced to invest $15.5 million to add an 82,000-square-foot wing assembly centre and the new facility is expected to open in July 2020. The new assembly centre would enhance production efficiency by allowing more wings to be assembled at the same time and additional storage for service parts to support the growing fleet in service around the world.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Moffett |first1=Margaret |title=HondaJet plans $15.5M expansion at PTIA |url=https://www.bizjournals.com/triad/news/2019/05/20/hondajet-plans-15-5m-expansion-at-ptia.html |accessdate=24 January 2020 |work=www.bizjournals.com |date=20 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n===HondaJet Elite===\nAfter the jet was certified in December 2015, Honda engineers started to work on the improved HondaJet Elite, with an expanded performance envelope, improved interior  and updated flight deck.<!--ref name=AIN15Jun2018/--> Range is increased by {{cvt|214|to|1,437|nmi|km}} with an auxiliary fuel tank and aerodynamic improvements.<!--ref name=AIN15Jun2018/--> The horizontal stabilizer tips are extended slightly and hinge gaps tightened up, allowing energized flow over the stabilizer without its vortex generators.<!--ref name=AIN15Jun2018/--> The type certificate was amended by the FAA on 2 May  2018, and soon followed by EASA.<ref name=AIN15Jun2018>{{cite web |last1=Thurber |first1=Matt |title=HondaJet Elite is Honda's Newest Light Jet |date= 15 Jun 2018 |url=https://www.ainonline.com/aviation-news/business-aviation/2018-06-15/hondajet-elite-hondas-newest-light-jet |website=Aviation International News}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2018, 30 months after the introduction, the $5.2 million (as of 2018) HondaJet Elite was revealed before delivery began in August.<!--ref name=Flight28may2018--> Its [[Elevator (aeronautics)|elevator]] authority is increased to reduce its takeoff roll by {{cvt|400|feet}}, reducing the [[Cessna Citation M2]]'s range and take-off advantages.<!--<ref name=Flight28may2018>-->  A new [[engine inlet]] reduces vibration and cabin noise, the lavatory receives a [[Seat belt|belted seat]] allowing a fifth passenger even with a galley and the [[Garmin G3000]]-based flight deck gets computed take-off distance and stability/[[angle of attack]] protection.<ref name=Flight28may2018>{{cite news |url= https://www.flightglobal.com/news/articles/ebace-hondajet-rolls-out-elite-upgrade-package-30-m-448937/ |title= HondaJet rolls out Elite upgrade package 30 months after EIS |date= 28 May 2018 |author= Stephen Trimble |work= Flightglobal}}</ref>\n\nIts payload is increased by over {{cvt|200|lb}}: {{convert|107|lb}} from the [[empty weight]] reduction and {{convert|100|lb}} from an increased [[maximum takeoff weight]] while {{cvt|16|USgal|l}} more of fuel tank fill unused space in the aft fuselage.<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.ainonline.com/aviation-news/business-aviation/2018-05-27/honda-aircraft-unveils-elite-hondajet |title= Honda Aircraft Unveils Elite HondaJet |author= Matt Thurber |date= May 27, 2018 |work= AIN online}}</ref> Honda began deliveries on August 7, 2018.<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.ainonline.com/aviation-news/business-aviation/2018-08-08/first-hondajet-elite-delivered |title= First HondaJet Elite Delivered |author= Chad Trautvetter |date= August 8, 2018 |work= AIN online}}</ref>\nThe upgrades are retrofitable for $250,000, including software updates and a 45&nbsp;kg (100&nbsp;lb) MTOW increase and take-off run reduction by 135&nbsp;m (443&nbsp;ft) to 1,064m thanks to a few inches span extension of the horizontal tailplane, removal of wing fences and vortex generators.<ref name=Flight15oct2018>{{cite news |url= https://www.flightglobal.com/news/articles/nbaa-performance-package-offered-for-baseline-hond-452700/ |title= NBAA: Performance package offered for baseline HondaJet |date= 15 Oct 2018 |author= Max Kingsley Jones |work= FlightGlobal}}</ref>\nAt a weight of {{cvt|9,500|lb}} and ISA+3&nbsp;\u00b0C, the HondaJet Elite cruises at Mach 0.676 or {{cvt|390|kn|km/h}} TAS, while burning {{cvt|570|lb}} per hour, better than book predictions.<ref>{{cite news |url= https://aviationweek.com/business-aviation/pilot-report-hondajet-elite |title= Pilot Report: HondaJet Elite Unparalleled attention to detail |date= Sep 19, 2019 |author= Fred George |work= Business & Commercial Aviation}}</ref>\n\n==Design==\n[[File:Paris Air Show 2017 HondaJet rear.jpg|thumb|Rear view of the aircraft, highlighting the [[Podded engine#Overwing podded engines|overwing podded engine]] configuration]]\n\n<!--airframe-->\nThe HondaJet is a [[Monoplane#Low wing|low-wing monoplane]], it has a mainly composite fuselage and an aluminium wing.\nEngines are mounted on pylons above the wing, a configuration designed to maximize cabin space,<ref name=opdo/> and achieve lower [[wave drag]] at a high [[Mach number]]. The nose and wing are designed for [[laminar flow]], and the main fuselage has a constant profile, making an eventual stretch easier. The combination of engine placement, wing and fuselage was achieved using [[Riemann solver|computer simulations]] and [[wind tunnel]]s.<ref name=fujTech>[[Michimasa Fujino|Fujino, Michimasa]]. \"[http://www.hondajet.com/Content/pdf/tech_papers/Journal_of_Aircraft_Vol42_No3_P755_P764_HondaJet.pdf Design and Development of the HondaJet]\" ''[[American Institute of Aeronautics and Astronautics#Journals|Journal of Aircraft]], Vol. 42, No. 3, May\u2013June 2005. Retrieved 28 March 2015.</ref><ref>Garrison, Peter. \"[https://books.google.com/books?id=LIyBivex-C4C&pg=PA84 Technicalities]\" page 83 ''Flying'', December 2006</ref>\nIt has a retractable tricycle landing gear with both main and nose landing gear single-wheeled.\n\n<!--engines-->\nThe aircraft is powered by two [[GE Honda HF120]] turbofans, developed with [[GE Aviation]] under the [[GE Honda Aero Engines|GE-Honda]] partnership.\nHonda began developing its own small turbofan engine, the HF118, in 1999, leading to the HF120. The HF120 was test-flown on a Cessna Citation CJ1.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ainonline.com/aviation-news/aviation-international-news/2010-01-28/approval-testing-continues-hf120-turbofan|title=Approval testing continues for HF120 turbofan|author=|date=|work=Aviation International News|accessdate=20 March 2015}}</ref> The engine features a single fan, a two-stage compressor and a two-stage turbine. The GE Honda HF120 received FAA type certification on 13 December 2013,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ainonline.com/aviation-news/business-aviation/2013-12-17/faa-certifies-ge-honda-aero-engines-hf120-turbofan|title=FAA Certifies GE Honda Aero Engines HF120 Turbofan|author=|date=|work=Aviation International News|accessdate=20 March 2015}}</ref> and production certification in 2015.<ref name=fg2015-03-27>{{citation |first=Stephen |last=Trimble |url=http://www.flightglobal.com/news/articles/hondajet-gains-provisional-type-certificate-deliveries-410669/ |title=HondaJet gains provisional type certificate, deliveries near |work=[[Flightglobal]] |publisher=Reed Business Information |date=27 March 2015 |accessdate=29 March 2015 }}</ref><ref name=ain2015-03-18/>\n\n<!--efficiency-->\nHonda claims that the combination of lightweight materials, aerodynamics and efficient engines gives the HondaJet up to 20% better fuel efficiency than similar aircraft.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2012/01/30/us-honda-jet-idUSTRE80T0F320120130|title=Honda out to shake up market with first jet next year|author=|date=|work=Reuters|accessdate=20 March 2015}}</ref> The jet consume 339 litres (89.5 gallons) of fuel per hour when cruising at 43,000 feet.<ref name=Buzz>{{cite web|last1=Gordon|first1=Lisa|title=Building the Buzz: HondaJet (Sep 15, 2017)|url=https://www.skiesmag.com/features/building-the-buzz/|website=Skiesmag.com|accessdate=21 September 2017}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Paris Air Show 2019, Le Bourget (SIAE1097).jpg|thumb|Interior of the HondaJet]]\n\n<!--interior-->\nThe interior dimensions are 5.43&nbsp;m (17.80&nbsp;ft) long, 1.52&nbsp;m (5.00&nbsp;ft) wide, and 1.47&nbsp;m (4.83&nbsp;ft) high, while the cabin is {{cvt|12.1|ft}} long besides the enclosed lavatory.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.hondajet.com/Content/pdf/hondajet-brochure.pdf |title= HondaJet brochure |publisher= Honda}}</ref> Total interior volume is {{cvt|324|cuft}}, and luggage capacity is {{cvt|66|cuft}}.<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.ainonline.com/aviation-news/aviation-international-news/2006-12-18/honda-reveals-new-details-about-cabin-its-jet |title=Honda reveals new details about the cabin of its jet |author= Matt Thurber |date= December 18, 2006 |work= AIN online}}</ref> \nThe aircraft is equipped with a [[touchscreen]] 3-display [[Garmin G3000]]<ref name=\"awHJ\"/> [[glass cockpit]] system. Most of the cockpit readouts are presented on flat-panel displays.\n[[File:HondajetPanel.jpg|thumb|right|Garmin 3000 Avionics for the HA-420]]\n\n===Accolades===\n[[Michimasa Fujino]] received the [[Business & Commercial Aviation]] - Vision Award (2008),<ref>{{cite web | url = https://aviationweek.com/awin/michimasa-fujino | title = Michimasa Fujino - President and CEO, Honda Aircraft Co. | work = Business & Commercial Aviation | date = December 1, 2008}}</ref>\nthe [[AIAA]] - Aircraft Design Award (2012),<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.aiaa.org/detail/award/award-aircraft-design-award |title=Aircraft Design Award |publisher=AIAA |year=2019 }}</ref>\nthe [[SAE International]] - [[Kelly Johnson (engineer)|Clarence L. (Kelly) Johnson]] Aerospace Vehicle Design and Development Award (2013),<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.sae.org/participate/awards/clarence-l-kelly-johnson-aerospace-vehicle-design-and-development-award |title=Clarence L. (Kelly) Johnson Aerospace Vehicle Design and Development Award |publisher=SAE International |access-date=June 24, 2019}}</ref>\nthe 2014 [[International Council of the Aeronautical Sciences|ICAS]] award  for Innovation in Aeronautics for leading the design,<ref>Trautvetter, Chad. \"[http://www.ainonline.com/aviation-news/ainalerts/2014-09-11/aeronautical-sciences-council-recognizes-honda-aircraft-leader-fujino Aeronautical Sciences Council Recognizes Honda Aircraft Leader Fujino]\" ''AINonline'', 11 September 2014</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.icas.org/media/pdf/Awards/Awardees%202014.pdf |title=ICAS Awardees 2014 |publisher=ICAS |year=2014 |format=PDF }}</ref> as well as a [[Living Legends of Aviation]] Industry Leader of the Year award.<ref>{{cite news|title=Honda Aircraft's Fujino given prestigious honour|url=https://www.wingsmagazine.com/news/honda-aircrafts-fujino-given-prestigious-honour-11524}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://living-legends-of-aviation.myshopify.com/pages/honorees |title=Honorees |publisher=Living Legends of Aviation |year=2017 }}</ref>\n\nThe HondaJet was included in the [[Robb Report]] - Best of the Best : Business Jets (2007),<ref>{{cite web | url = https://robbreport.com/motors/aviation/best-of-the-best-2007-business-jets-hondajet-239257/ | title = Best of the Best 2007: Business Jets: HondaJet | last = Grady | first = Mary | work = Robb Report | date = June 1, 2007}}</ref>\nin the [[Aviation Week & Space Technology]] - Techs To Watch (2010),<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.hondajet.com/Content/pdf/AviationWeek.pdf | title = Techs To Watch | last = Warwick | first = Graham | work = Aviation Week & Space Technology | date = January 25, 2010}}</ref>\nand in the 2014 'Best of What's New' by ''[[Popular Science]]'' magazine.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://bestofwhatsnew.popsci.com/honda-aircraft-company-hondajet |title=Aerospace - Honda Aircraft Company HondaJet |publisher=Bonnier Corporation |work=Popular Science |date=October 30, 2014}}</ref>\nand the [[Flying Magazine]] - Flying Innovation Award in 2017.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.flyingmag.com/hondajet-wins-flying-innovation-award|title=HondaJet Wins Flying Innovation Award|work=[[Flying (magazine)|Flying]]|date=July 25, 2017 }}</ref>\nThe [[Honda Aircraft Company]] received the [[AIAA]] Foundation Award for Excellence in 2018.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.aiaa.org/detail/award/award-aiaa-foundation-award-for-excellence | title = AIAA Foundation Award for Excellence | publisher = AIAA | year = 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Operational history==\n\nBy October 2018, the 92 aircraft in service had logged 20,000 hours with a 99.7% dispatch reliability.<ref name=Flight15oct2018/>\n\n==Specifications (Elite)==\n{{Aircraft specs\n|ref=HondaJet Elite Brochure<ref name=\"HondaJet_Elite_Brochure\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.hondajet.com/Content/pdf/HondaJetElite_Brochure.pdf |title=HondaJet Elite Brochure |accessdate=2019-06-06 |publisher=[[Honda Aircraft Company]] |page=8}}</ref>\n|prime units?=imp<!-- imp or kts first for US aircraft, and UK aircraft pre-metrification, \nmet(ric) first for all others. You MUST choose a format, or no specifications will show -->\n<!--\n        General characteristics\n-->\n|genhide=\n\n|crew=1-2\n|capacity=7 occupants, crew included\n\n|length m=12.99\n|length ft=\n|length in=\n|length note=\n|span m=12.12\n|span ft=\n|span in=\n|span note=\n|height m=4.54\n|height ft=\n|height in=\n|height note=\n|wing area sqm=\n|wing area sqft=\n|wing area note=\n|airfoil=\n|empty weight kg=\n|empty weight lb=\n|empty weight note=\n|gross weight kg=\n|gross weight lb=\n|gross weight note=\n|max takeoff weight kg=4854\n|max takeoff weight lb=\n|max takeoff weight note=<ref name=HondaJet-TCDS>{{Cite web |url=https://rgl.faa.gov/Regulatory_and_Guidance_Library/rgMakeModel.nsf/0/0a252b01e4fe31f7862583ad0075f4e5/$FILE/A00018AT_Rev_7.pdf |title=Type Certificate Data Sheet No. A00018AT Rev. 7 |date=2019-02-13 |publisher=[[Federal Aviation Administration]] |accessdate=2019-06-06 |page=2}}</ref>\n|fuel capacity=\n|more general=\n<!--\n        Powerplant\n-->\n|eng1 number=2\n|eng1 name=[[GE Honda HF120]]\n|eng1 type=[[turbofan]]\n|eng1 lbf=2,050\n|eng1 hp=<!-- prop engines -->\n|eng1 shp=<!-- prop engines -->\n|eng1 note=\n|power original=\n|thrust original=\n<!--\n        Performance\n-->\n|perfhide=\n\n|max speed kmh=\n|max speed mph=\n|max speed kts=\n|max speed note=\n|max speed mach=<!-- supersonic aircraft -->\n|cruise speed kmh=782\n|cruise speed mph=\n|cruise speed kts=\n|cruise speed note=FL300\n|stall speed kmh=\n|stall speed mph=\n|stall speed kts=\n|stall speed note=\n|never exceed speed kmh=\n|never exceed speed mph=\n|never exceed speed kts=\n|never exceed speed note=\n|minimum control speed kmh=\n|minimum control speed mph=\n|minimum control speed kts=\n|minimum control speed note=\n|range km=2661\n|range miles=\n|range nmi=\n|range note=NBAA IFR Range with 4 occupants\n|endurance=<!-- if range unknown -->\n|ceiling m=\n|ceiling ft=43000\n|ceiling n