{"title_page": "Tsutomu Miyazaki", "text_new": "{{refimprove|date=May 2019}}\n{{Infobox serial killer\n|name=Tsutomu Miyazaki\n|image=Kermit the Frog.jpg\n|caption=Miyazaki, prior to their execution\n|birth_name=\n|birth_date= August 21, 1962\n|birth_place=[[Itsukaichi, Tokyo|Itsukaichi]], [[Tokyo]], [[Japan]]\n|death_date={{death date and age|2008|6|17|1962|8|21}}\n|cause= [[Hanging|Execution by hanging]]\n|parents = Katsumi Miyazaki (father) \n|victims=4\n|country=Japan\n|alias=The Otaku Murderer<br>The Little Girl Murderer<br>Dracula<br>Rat Man\n|states=[[Saitama Prefecture|Saitama]], [[Tokyo]]\n|conviction= [[Murder]]\n|beginyear=1988\n|endyear=1989\n|apprehended=July 23, 1989\n|sentence=[[Capital punishment|Death]]\n|death_place=[[Tokyo Detention House]], [[Katsushika]], Japan\n|criminal_status=Executed}}\n\n{{nihongo|'''Tsutomu Miyazaki'''|\u5bae\ufa11 \u52e4|''Miyazaki Tsutomu''|extra=August 21, 1962 \u2013 June 17, 2008}}, also known as '''the [[Otaku]] Murderer''' or '''the Little Girl Murderer''', was a Japanese [[serial killer]], [[Human cannibalism|cannibal]], [[Child sexual abuse|child rapist]] and [[Necrophilia|necrophile]] who abducted and murdered four young girls\u2014and sexually molested their corpses\u2014in the [[Saitama Prefecture|Saitama]] and [[Tokyo]] prefectures between August 1988 and June 1989.<ref>{{cite magazine|date=1997|title=\"The man, Tsutomu Miyazaki, kidnapped and killed four girls aged between four and seven in Tokyo and Saitama, north of Tokyo...\"|url=https://www.google.com/books/edition/Asian_Recorder/OIxtAAAAMAAJ|magazine=Asian Recorder|location=Google Books|publisher=K. K. Thomas at Recorder Press|volume=43|page=|access-date=26 December 2019}}</ref> His crimes included not only kidnapping, murder, and necrophilia, but also [[vampirism]] and the preservation of body parts as trophies.<ref name=abc>{{cite news|url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2008-06-18/japan-confirms-execution-of-cannibal-killer/2475810|title=Japan executes notorious cannibal killer|publisher=[[Australian Broadcasting Corporation|ABC]]|date=17 June 2008|access-date=9 May 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.yomiuri.co.jp/dy/national/20080618TDY02306.htm|title=Miyazaki unrepentant to the last / Serial child killer goes to execution without apologizing or explaining his thinking|work=[[Yomiuri Shimbun]]|location=Tokyo|date=18 June 2008|access-date=18 June 2008|archive-url=https://archive.is/20080621044230/http://www.yomiuri.co.jp/dy/national/20080618TDY02306.htm|archive-date=21 June 2008}}</ref>\n\nMiyazaki was arrested in 1989 in [[Hachi\u014dji]], Tokyo after being confronted by a father who had found Miyazaki taking nude photographs of one of his young daughters. After Miyazaki was apprehended, it was discovered that he had an extensive collection of [[anime]] and [[Horror fiction|horror]] videotapes, causing a [[moral panic]] against ''otaku''. Though psychiatrists diagnosed Miyazaki as having one or more [[personality disorder]]s, he was determined to be aware of his crimes and their consequences, and was sentenced to [[death by hanging]] in 1997. He was executed in 2008.\n\n==Background==\nMiyazaki was [[premature birth|born premature]] and had a birth defect where his hand joints were fused together, preventing him from being able to bend his wrists upwards.<ref name=charlest>{{cite web|url=http://www.charlest.whipple.net/miyazaki.html|title=The Silencing of the Lambs|author=Charles T. Whipple|access-date=5 March 2008|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070818192957/http://www.charlest.whipple.net/miyazaki.html|archive-date=18 August 2007}}</ref> Due to his deformity, he was ostracized when he attended Itsukaichi Elementary School<!-- Located where?-->, and consequently kept to himself. He attended Meidai Nakano High School in [[Nakano, Tokyo]], and was a star student until his grades dropped dramatically. He was ranked 40 out of 56 in his class, and did not receive the customary admission to [[Meiji University]]. Instead of studying [[English language|English]] and becoming a teacher as he originally intended, he attended a local junior college and studied to become a photo technician.<ref name=charlest/>\n\nIn the mid-1980s, Miyazaki moved back into his parent's house near his father's print shop, sharing a room with his elder sister. Although Miyazaki's family was highly influential in [[Itsukaichi, Tokyo|Itsukaichi]], where his father owned a newspaper, Miyazaki expressed no desire to take over his father's job. After his arrest, Miyazaki would say that what he really craved was \"being listened to about his problems\" but believed that his parents, more worried about the material than the sentimental\u2014\"would have not heard [him]; [he] would've been ignored\".<ref name=lyon>{{cite book|authors=Lyon, Samantha; Dr Daphne Tan|title=Supernatural Serial Killers: What makes them murder?|publisher=Arcturus Publishing|year=2015|isbn=1784281328}}</ref> In the same confession, he said that by this period in his life he had begun to consider [[suicide]].\n\nMiyazaki was rejected by his two younger sisters, and felt he only received support from his grandfather. In May 1988, his grandfather died. This served to deepen his [[depression (mood)|depression]] and isolated him even further.<ref name=lyon/> In an attempt to \"retain something from him\", Miyazaki ate part of his grandfather's ashes. A few weeks later, one of his sisters caught him watching her while she was taking a shower. When she told him to leave, Miyazaki attacked her. When his mother learned of the incident and demanded that he spend more time working, and less time with his videos, he attacked her as well.<ref name=lyon/>\n\n==Murders==\nBetween August 1988 and June 1989, Miyazaki [[mutilation|mutilated]] and killed four girls between the ages of four and seven, and [[Child sexual abuse|sexually molested]] [[Necrophilia|their corpses]]. He drank the blood of one victim and ate a part of her hand.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.scotsman.com/news-2-15012/serial-child-killer-hanged-as-japan-steps-up-death-penalty-1-1173292|title=Serial child-killer hanged as Japan steps up death penalty|work=[[The Scotsman]]|location=Edinburgh|date=17 June 2008|access-date=9 May 2019}}</ref> These crimes\u2014which prior to Miyazaki's apprehension were named the \"Little Girl Murders\" and later the {{nihongo|Tokyo/Saitama Serial Kidnapping Murders of Little Girls|\u6771\u4eac\u30fb\u57fc\u7389\u9023\u7d9a\u5e7c\u5973\u8a98\u62d0\u6bba\u4eba\u4e8b\u4ef6|T\u014dky\u014d Saitama renzoku y\u014djo y\u016bkai satsujin jiken}}\u2014shocked [[Saitama Prefecture]], which had few crimes against children.\n\nDuring the day, Miyazaki was, by all accounts, a mild-mannered individual. Outside of work, he randomly selected children to kill. He wrote to the families of his victims, sending them letters recalling the details of his murders. Police found that the families of the victims had something else in common: all received silent [[Nuisance call|nuisance phone calls]]. Miyazaki would not speak a word during these calls, instead simply breathing heavily. If they did not answer Miyazaki\u2019s calls, he would call repeatedly; sometimes their phones would ring up to 20 minutes.\n\nOn August 22, 1988, one day after Miyazaki's 26th birthday, Mari Konno, a four-year-old girl, vanished while playing at a friend's house. After failed attempts to find her, Konno's father contacted the police. Miyazaki had led Konno into his black [[Nissan Langley]] and abducted her. He drove westward of [[Tokyo]] and parked the car under a bridge in a wooded area. There he sat alongside the girl for a half-hour before murdering her. He then engaged in sexual acts with the corpse and left her corpse in the hills near his home. He took her clothes with him and departed. He allowed Konno's corpse to [[decompose]] for a while before later returning to remove the hands and feet, which he kept in his closet. These were recovered upon his arrest. He charred her remaining bones in his furnace, ground them into powder, and sent them to her family in a box, along with several of her teeth, photos of her clothes, and a postcard which read: \"Mari. Cremated. Bones. Investigate. Prove.\"<ref>{{cite book|author=McQueen, Victor|title=The World's Worst Serial Killers: Monsters whose crimes shocked the world|publisher=Arcturus Publishing|year=2015|isbn=1784281484}}</ref>\n\nOn October 3, 1988, Miyazaki was driving along a rural road when he spotted seven-year-old Masami Yoshizawa. He offered her a ride, and she accepted. He then drove to the same place he had killed Konno, and killed Yoshizawa. He engaged in sexual acts with the corpse, and took the girl's clothes with him when he departed.<ref name=keller>{{cite book|author=Keller, Robert|title=Beyond Evil|year=2016|isbn=1536507644}}</ref>\n\nOn December 12, 1988, four-year-old Erika Namba was returning home from a friend's house when Miyazaki kidnapped her, forcing her into his car. He drove to a parking lot in [[Naguri, Saitama]], forced her to remove her clothes in the back seat, and began to take pictures of her. After killing her, he tied her hands and feet behind her back, covered her with a bed sheet, and placed the body in his car's trunk. He disposed of the girl's clothes in a wooded area and left the body in the adjoining parking lot. Miyazaki sent a [[postcard]] to her family, assembled using words cut out of magazines: \"Erika. Cold. Cough. Throat. Rest. Death.\"<ref name=keller/>\n\nOn June 6, 1989, Miyazaki convinced five-year-old Ayako Nomoto to allow him to take pictures of her. He then led her into his car and murdered her. He covered the corpse with a bed sheet and placed her in the trunk of his car, taking the body to his apartment. He spent the next two days engaging in sexual acts with the corpse, taking pictures of it in various positions, and filming it.<ref name=keller/>\n\nWhen the body began to decompose, Miyazaki dismembered it, abandoning the torso in a cemetery and the head in the nearby hills. He kept the hands, from which he drank blood and ate part of them. Fearing that the police would find the corpse, he returned to the [[cemetery]] and the hills two weeks later and carried the remains back to his apartment, where he hid them in his closet.\n\n==Arrest==\nOn July 23, 1989, Miyazaki saw two sisters playing in a park in [[Hachi\u014dji]], Tokyo. He managed to separate the younger of the sisters from the older one, who stayed behind. The sisters' father arrived shortly after to find Miyazaki taking photographs of the younger daughter, who he had convinced to strip nude. The father attacked Miyazaki, but was unable to restrain him.<ref>https://www.abc.net.au/news/2008-06-18/japan-confirms-execution-of-cannibal-killer/2475810</ref><ref name=keller /> After fleeing on foot, Miyazaki eventually returned to the park to retrieve his car, whereupon he was arrested by police responding to a call by the father. A search of Miyazaki's two-room bungalow produced 5,763 videotapes, some containing [[anime]] and [[Slasher film|slasher]] films (later used as reasoning for his crimes). Interspersed among them was video footage and pictures of his victims. He was also reported to be a fan of [[horror film]]s, of which he had a collection. Miyazaki, who retained a perpetually calm and collected demeanor during his trial, appeared indifferent to his capture.<ref>{{cite news|author=Schoenberger, Karl|url=https://www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-1989-09-09-mn-1579-story.html|title=Sordid Serial-Killing Case Exposes the Other Side of Innocence in Japan|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|date=9 September 1989}}</ref>\n\n==Moral panic==\nThe [[News media|media]] called him \"The [[Otaku]] Murderer\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://scaredyet.net/the-otaku-killer-miyazaki-tsutomu/|title=The Otaku Killer: Miyazaki Tsutomu|author=Oliviera, James|date=3 January 2010|access-date=7 January 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150107074646/http://scaredyet.net/the-otaku-killer-miyazaki-tsutomu/|archive-date=7 January 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> His killings caused a [[moral panic]] against otaku, accusing anime and horror films of making him a murderer. Various newspapers claimed that Miyazaki had retreated into a fantasy world of manga as a result of his neglected upbringing.<ref name=Kinsella>{{cite journal|last=Kinsella|first=Sharon|year=1998|title=Amateur Manga Subculture and the Otaku Panic|journal=Journal of Japanese Studies|volume=24|issue=2|pages=308\u20139|url=http://www.kinsellaresearch.com/new/Japanese%20Subculture.pdf|publisher=Washington University Press}}</ref> Keigo Okonogi, a [[psychoanalyst]] at [[Tokyo International University]], told the ''Sh\u016bkan Post'' that:\n\n{{quote |text=\nThe danger of a whole generation of youth who do not even experience the most primary two- or three-way relationship between themselves and their mother and father, and who cannot make the transition from a fantasy world of videos and manga to reality, is now extreme.<ref name=Kinsella/>\n}}\n\nThese reports were disputed. In [[Eiji \u014ctsuka]]'s book on the crime, he argued that Miyazaki's collection of pornography was probably added or amended by a photographer in order to highlight his perversity.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www1.odn.ne.jp/kamiya-ta/gisi.html|script-title=ja:\u5927\u585a\u82f1\u5fd7\u300e\u300c\u304a\u305f\u304f\u300d\u306e\u7cbe\u795e\u53f2\u300f\uff5e\u307c\u304f\u304c\u4e2d\u5b66\u6642\u4ee3\u306b\u3064\u304f\u3063\u305f\u300c\u507d\u53f2\u300d\u306b\u3064\u3044\u3066|trans-title=Hideshi Otsuka \"Psychical History of Otaku\"-\"About the \"fake history\" I made during junior high school\"|language=ja|author=Kousetsu Kamiya|access-date=9 May 2019}}</ref> Another critic, Fumiya Ichihashi, suspected the released information was playing up to public stereotypes and fears about otaku, as the police knew they would help cement a conviction.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sunfield.ne.jp/~mike/books/nonfiction/crime/author/ichihashi_fumiya/miyazaki.htm|title=Miyazaki Tsutomu Jiken|publisher=Japanese Literature Webring|access-date=9 May 2019}}</ref> Sharon Kinsella asserts that large collections of manga and videos were typical in the rooms of youths living in the Tokyo area at the time.<ref name=Kinsella/>\n\n==Trial and execution==\nThe trial began on March 30, 1990. Often talking nonsensically, Miyazaki blamed his actions on \"Rat Man\", an [[alter ego]] who Miyazaki claimed forced him to kill; he spent time during the trial drawing \"Rat Man\" in cartoon form.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/world/asia/article4156285.ece|title=Japanese 'cannibal killer' executed in Tokyo |work=[[The Times]]|date=17 June 2008|access-date=17 June 2008|location=London|author=Lewis, Leo|archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/60qqMCSKQ?url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/world/asia/article4156285.ece |archive-date=11 August 2011|url-status=live}}</ref> Miyazaki's father refused to pay for his son's legal defense and committed suicide in 1994.<ref name=abc/> \n\nThe seven-year trial focused on Miyazaki's mental state at the time of the murders. Under Japanese law, people of unsound minds are not subject to punishment, and the feeble-minded are entitled to reduced sentences. Three teams of court-appointed expert psychiatrists came to differing conclusions about Miyazaki's ability to tell right from wrong. Two teams determined him to be feeble-minded\u2014one team concluding that he was [[schizophrenia|schizophrenic]], the other that he had [[multiple personality disorder]]. A third team found that although Miyazaki had a personality disorder, he was still capable of taking responsibility for his actions.<ref name=\"JapanTimes1997-04-14\">{{cite news |title=Serial child-killer Miyazaki gets death sentence |url=https://www.japantimes.co.jp/news/1997/04/14/national/serial-child-killer-miyazaki-gets-death-sentence/ |access-date=27 June 2019 |work=[[The Japan Times]] |date=14 April 1997}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Tokyo District Court]] judged him aware of the magnitude and consequences of his crimes and therefore accountable. He was sentenced to death on April 14, 1997.<ref name=\"JapanTimes1997-04-14\"/> His death sentence was upheld by both the [[Tokyo High Court]], on June 28, 2001, and the [[Supreme Court of Japan|Supreme Court of Justice]] on January 17, 2006.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://english.people.com.cn/200601/17/eng20060117_236139.html|title=Japan's Supreme Court upholds death penalty on child killer|work=[[People's Daily]]|location=Beijing|agency=[[Xinhua]]|date=17 January 2006|access-date=9 May 2019}}</ref>\n\nHe described his serial murders as an \"act of benevolence\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://jmjp.jp/topics/2008/06/post_492.html|script-title=ja:\u7570\u5e38\u306a\u72af\u7f6a\u3001\u907a\u65cf\u3078\u306e\u8b1d\u7f6a\u3082\u306a\u304f\u2026\u5bae\u5d0e\u6b7b\u5211\u56da|language=ja|location=Tokyo|date=17 June 2008|access-date=9 May 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/asia/japan/2144503/Nerd-cult-murderer-executed.html|title=Nerd cult murderer executed|work=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|date=17 June 2008|access-date=8 May 2019|location=London|author=Ryall, Julian}}</ref> Child killer [[Kaoru Kobayashi (murderer)|Kaoru Kobayashi]] described himself as \"the next Tsutomu Miyazaki or [[Mamoru Takuma]]\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.japantimes.co.jp/news/2005/04/19/national/defendant-admits-abducting-and-killing-schoolgirl-in-nara/|title=Defendant admits abducting and killing schoolgirl in Nara|work=[[The Japan Times]]|agency=[[Kyodo News]] |access-date=9 May 2019|date=19 April 2005}}</ref> Miyazaki stated, \"I won't allow him to call himself 'the second Tsutomu Miyazaki' when he hasn't even undergone a psychiatric examination.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.yomiuri.co.jp/dy/national/20080618TDY02306.htm|title=Miyazaki unrepentant to the last / Serial child killer goes to execution without apologizing or explaining his thinking|work=[[Yomiuri Shimbun]]|location=Tokyo|date=18 June 2008|access-date=18 June 2008|archive-url=https://archive.is/20080621044230/http://www.yomiuri.co.jp/dy/national/20080618TDY02306.htm|archive-date=21 June 2008}}</ref>\n\n[[Minister of Justice (Japan)|Minister of Justice]] [[Kunio Hatoyama]] signed his death warrant and Miyazaki was hanged on June 17, 2008.<ref>{{cite news|author=Yamaguchi, Mari|url=https://www.chron.com/news/nation-world/article/Japan-executes-3-including-serial-killer-of-1767054.php|title=Japan executes 3, including serial killer who mutilated young girls|work=[[Houston Chronicle]]|agency=[[Associated Press]]|date=2008-06-17|location=Neuilly-sur-Seine, France|access-date=9 May 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2008/06/17/AR2008061701131.html|title=Japan Hangs Three Killers As Pace of Executions Rises|work=[[The Washington Post]]|date=2008-06-17|access-date=9 May 2019|author=Harden, Blaine}}</ref> The unusual swiftness of his execution as well as its timing soon after the [[Akihabara massacre]] prompted questions regarding the two incidents;<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/06/17/world/asia/17iht-japan.2.13771425.html|title=Japan Hangs Three Convicted Murderers|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=17 June 2008|access-date=9 May 2019|author=Foster, Martin}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nikkansports.com/general/news/p-gn-tp0-20080618-373365.html|script-title=ja:\u7121\u5dee\u5225\u6bba\u4eba\u3078\u306e\u6291\u6b62\u52b9\u679c\uff1f\u5bae\u5d0e\u52e4\u6b7b\u5211\u57f7\u884c |language=Japanese|work=[[Nikkan Sports]]|location=Tokyo|date=18 June 2008|access-date=18 June 2008}}</ref> the [[Ministry of Justice (Japan)|Ministry of Justice]] had no comment.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.j-cast.com/2008/06/17021964.html|script-title=ja:\u5bae\u5d0e\u6b7b\u5211\u56da\u306b\u300c\u30b9\u30d4\u30fc\u30c9\u300d\u6b7b\u5211\u57f7\u884c\u3000\u56c1\u304b\u308c\u308b\u300c\u79cb\u8449\u539f\u4e8b\u4ef6\u300d\u306e\u5f71\u97ff\uff1f|language=ja|publisher=J-CAST|date=17 June 2008|access-date=9 May 2019}}</ref> [[Ry\u016bz\u014d Saki]] said, \"His trial was long\" and that he was \"not willing to criticize Hatoyama\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nikkansports.com/general/news/p-gn-tp0-20080618-373366.html|script-title=ja:\u4f5c\u5bb6\u4f50\u6728\u9686\u4e09\u3055\u3093\u300c\u9577\u3044\u88c1\u5224\u3060\u3063\u305f\u300d|language=ja|work=[[Nikkan Sports]]|location=Tokyo|date=18 June 2008|access-date=18 June 2008|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080619110206/http://www.nikkansports.com/general/news/p-gn-tp0-20080618-373366.html|archive-date=19 June 2008}}</ref>\n\n==Victims==\n#{{nihongo|'''Mari Konno'''|\u4eca\u91ce\u771f\u7406|''Konno Mari''}}: Four years old\n#{{nihongo|'''Masami Yoshizawa'''|\u5409\u6ca2\u6b63\u7f8e|''Yoshizawa Masami''}}: Seven years old\n#{{nihongo|'''Erika Namba'''|\u96e3\u6ce2\u7d75\u68a8\u9999|''Namba Erika''}}: Four years old\n#{{nihongo|'''Ayako Nomoto'''|\u91ce\u672c\u7dbe\u5b50|''Nomoto Ayako''}}: Five years old\n\n==See also==\n*[[Kaoru Kobayashi (murderer)|Kaoru Kobayashi]]\n*[[Insanity defense]]\n*[[Capital punishment in Japan]]\n*[[List of serial killers by country]]\n*[[John Wayne Gacy]]\n*[[Westley Allen Dodd]]\n*[[Richard Ramirez]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Miyazaki, Tsutomu}}\n[[Category:1962 births]]\n[[Category:2008 deaths]]\n[[Category:21st-century executions by Japan]]\n[[Category:Executed Japanese serial killers]]\n[[Category:Japanese cannibals]]\n[[Category:Japanese murderers of children]]\n[[Category:Japanese people convicted of child sexual abuse]]\n[[Category:Japanese people convicted of murder]]\n[[Category:Japanese people with disabilities]]\n[[Category:Male serial killers]]\n[[Category:Murder in 1988]]\n[[Category:Necrophiles]]\n[[Category:Otaku]]\n[[Category:People convicted of murder by Japan]]\n[[Category:People with personality disorders]]\n[[Category:People executed by Japan by hanging]]\n[[Category:People with dissociative identity disorder]]\n[[Category:People from Western Tokyo]]\n[[Category:People with schizophrenia]]\n[[Category:Vampirism (crime)]]\n", "text_old": "{{refimprove|date=May 2019}}\n{{Infobox serial killer\n|name=Tsutomu Miyazaki\n|image=Tsutomu_Miyazaki.jpg\n|caption=\n|birth_name=\n|birth_date= August 21, 1962\n|birth_place=[[Itsukaichi, Tokyo|Itsukaichi]], [[Tokyo]], [[Japan]]\n|death_date={{death date and age|2008|6|17|1962|8|21}}\n|cause= [[Hanging|Execution by hanging]]\n|parents = Katsumi Miyazaki (father) \n|victims=4\n|country=Japan\n|alias=The Otaku Murderer<br>The Little Girl Murderer<br>Dracula<br>Rat Man\n|states=[[Saitama Prefecture|Saitama]], [[Tokyo]]\n|conviction= [[Murder]]\n|beginyear=1988\n|endyear=1989\n|apprehended=July 23, 1989\n|sentence=[[Capital punishment|Death]]\n|death_place=[[Tokyo Detention House]], [[Katsushika]], Japan\n|criminal_status=Executed}}\n\n{{nihongo|'''Tsutomu Miyazaki'''|\u5bae\ufa11 \u52e4|''Miyazaki Tsutomu''|extra=August 21, 1962 \u2013 June 17, 2008}}, also known as '''the [[Otaku]] Murderer''' or '''the Little Girl Murderer''', was a Japanese [[serial killer]], [[Human cannibalism|cannibal]], [[Child sexual abuse|child rapist]] and [[Necrophilia|necrophile]] who abducted and murdered four young girls\u2014and sexually molested their corpses\u2014in the [[Saitama Prefecture|Saitama]] and [[Tokyo]] prefectures between August 1988 and June 1989.<ref>{{cite magazine|date=1997|title=\"The man, Tsutomu Miyazaki, kidnapped and killed four girls aged between four and seven in Tokyo and Saitama, north of Tokyo...\"|url=https://www.google.com/books/edition/Asian_Recorder/OIxtAAAAMAAJ|magazine=Asian Recorder|location=Google Books|publisher=K. K. Thomas at Recorder Press|volume=43|page=|access-date=26 December 2019}}</ref> His crimes included not only kidnapping, murder, and necrophilia, but also [[vampirism]] and the preservation of body parts as trophies.<ref name=abc>{{cite news|url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2008-06-18/japan-confirms-execution-of-cannibal-killer/2475810|title=Japan executes notorious cannibal killer|publisher=[[Australian Broadcasting Corporation|ABC]]|date=17 June 2008|access-date=9 May 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.yomiuri.co.jp/dy/national/20080618TDY02306.htm|title=Miyazaki unrepentant to the last / Serial child killer goes to execution without apologizing or explaining his thinking|work=[[Yomiuri Shimbun]]|location=Tokyo|date=18 June 2008|access-date=18 June 2008|archive-url=https://archive.is/20080621044230/http://www.yomiuri.co.jp/dy/national/20080618TDY02306.htm|archive-date=21 June 2008}}</ref>\n\nMiyazaki was arrested in 1989 in [[Hachi\u014dji]], Tokyo after being confronted by a father who had found Miyazaki taking nude photographs of one of his young daughters. After Miyazaki was apprehended, it was discovered that he had an extensive collection of [[anime]] and [[Horror fiction|horror]] videotapes, causing a [[moral panic]] against ''otaku''. Though psychiatrists diagnosed Miyazaki as having one or more [[personality disorder]]s, he was determined to be aware of his crimes and their consequences, and was sentenced to [[death by hanging]] in 1997. He was executed in 2008.\n\n==Background==\nMiyazaki was [[premature birth|born premature]] and had a birth defect where his hand joints were fused together, preventing him from being able to bend his wrists upwards.<ref name=charlest>{{cite web|url=http://www.charlest.whipple.net/miyazaki.html|title=The Silencing of the Lambs|author=Charles T. Whipple|access-date=5 March 2008|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070818192957/http://www.charlest.whipple.net/miyazaki.html|archive-date=18 August 2007}}</ref> Due to his deformity, he was ostracized when he attended Itsukaichi Elementary School<!-- Located where?-->, and consequently kept to himself. He attended Meidai Nakano High School in [[Nakano, Tokyo]], and was a star student until his grades dropped dramatically. He was ranked 40 out of 56 in his class, and did not receive the customary admission to [[Meiji University]]. Instead of studying [[English language|English]] and becoming a teacher as he originally intended, he attended a local junior college and studied to become a photo technician.<ref name=charlest/>\n\nIn the mid-1980s, Miyazaki moved back into his parent's house near his father's print shop, sharing a room with his elder sister. Although Miyazaki's family was highly influential in [[Itsukaichi, Tokyo|Itsukaichi]], where his father owned a newspaper, Miyazaki expressed no desire to take over his father's job. After his arrest, Miyazaki would say that what he really craved was \"being listened to about his problems\" but believed that his parents, more worried about the material than the sentimental\u2014\"would have not heard [him]; [he] would've been ignored\".<ref name=lyon>{{cite book|authors=Lyon, Samantha; Dr Daphne Tan|title=Supernatural Serial Killers: What makes them murder?|publisher=Arcturus Publishing|year=2015|isbn=1784281328}}</ref> In the same confession, he said that by this period in his life he had begun to consider [[suicide]].\n\nMiyazaki was rejected by his two younger sisters, and felt he only received support from his grandfather. In May 1988, his grandfather died. This served to deepen his [[depression (mood)|depression]] and isolated him even further.<ref name=lyon/> In an attempt to \"retain something from him\", Miyazaki ate part of his grandfather's ashes. A few weeks later, one of his sisters caught him watching her while she was taking a shower. When she told him to leave, Miyazaki attacked her. When his mother learned of the incident and demanded that he spend more time working, and less time with his videos, he attacked her as well.<ref name=lyon/>\n\n==Murders==\nBetween August 1988 and June 1989, Miyazaki [[mutilation|mutilated]] and killed four girls between the ages of four and seven, and [[Child sexual abuse|sexually molested]] [[Necrophilia|their corpses]]. He drank the blood of one victim and ate a part of her hand.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.scotsman.com/news-2-15012/serial-child-killer-hanged-as-japan-steps-up-death-penalty-1-1173292|title=Serial child-killer hanged as Japan steps up death penalty|work=[[The Scotsman]]|location=Edinburgh|date=17 June 2008|access-date=9 May 2019}}</ref> These crimes\u2014which prior to Miyazaki's apprehension were named the \"Little Girl Murders\" and later the {{nihongo|Tokyo/Saitama Serial Kidnapping Murders of Little Girls|\u6771\u4eac\u30fb\u57fc\u7389\u9023\u7d9a\u5e7c\u5973\u8a98\u62d0\u6bba\u4eba\u4e8b\u4ef6|T\u014dky\u014d Saitama renzoku y\u014djo y\u016bkai satsujin jiken}}\u2014shocked [[Saitama Prefecture]], which had few crimes against children.\n\nDuring the day, Miyazaki was, by all accounts, a mild-mannered individual. Outside of work, he randomly selected children to kill. He wrote to the families of his victims, sending them letters recalling the details of his murders. Police found that the families of the victims had something else in common: all received silent [[Nuisance call|nuisance phone calls]]. Miyazaki would not speak a word during these calls, instead simply breathing heavily. If they did not answer Miyazaki\u2019s calls, he would call repeatedly; sometimes their phones would ring up to 20 minutes.\n\nOn August 22, 1988, one day after Miyazaki's 26th birthday, Mari Konno, a four-year-old girl, vanished while playing at a friend's house. After failed attempts to find her, Konno's father contacted the police. Miyazaki had led Konno into his black [[Nissan Langley]] and abducted her. He drove westward of [[Tokyo]] and parked the car under a bridge in a wooded area. There he sat alongside the girl for a half-hour before murdering her. He then engaged in sexual acts with the corpse and left her corpse in the hills near his home. He took her clothes with him and departed. He allowed Konno's corpse to [[decompose]] for a while before later returning to remove the hands and feet, which he kept in his closet. These were recovered upon his arrest. He charred her remaining bones in his furnace, ground them into powder, and sent them to her family in a box, along with several of her teeth, photos of her clothes, and a postcard which read: \"Mari. Cremated. Bones. Investigate. Prove.\"<ref>{{cite book|author=McQueen, Victor|title=The World's Worst Serial Killers: Monsters whose crimes shocked the world|publisher=Arcturus Publishing|year=2015|isbn=1784281484}}</ref>\n\nOn October 3, 1988, Miyazaki was driving along a rural road when he spotted seven-year-old Masami Yoshizawa. He offered her a ride, and she accepted. He then drove to the same place he had killed Konno, and killed Yoshizawa. He engaged in sexual acts with the corpse, and took the girl's clothes with him when he departed.<ref name=keller>{{cite book|author=Keller, Robert|title=Beyond Evil|year=2016|isbn=1536507644}}</ref>\n\nOn December 12, 1988, four-year-old Erika Namba was returning home from a friend's house when Miyazaki kidnapped her, forcing her into his car. He drove to a parking lot in [[Naguri, Saitama]], forced her to remove her clothes in the back seat, and began to take pictures of her. After killing her, he tied her hands and feet behind her back, covered her with a bed sheet, and placed the body in his car's trunk. He disposed of the girl's clothes in a wooded area and left the body in the adjoining parking lot. Miyazaki sent a [[postcard]] to her family, assembled using words cut out of magazines: \"Erika. Cold. Cough. Throat. Rest. Death.\"<ref name=keller/>\n\nOn June 6, 1989, Miyazaki convinced five-year-old Ayako Nomoto to allow him to take pictures of her. He then led her into his car and murdered her. He covered the corpse with a bed sheet and placed her in the trunk of his car, taking the body to his apartment. He spent the next two days engaging in sexual acts with the corpse, taking pictures of it in various positions, and filming it.<ref name=keller/>\n\nWhen the body began to decompose, Miyazaki dismembered it, abandoning the torso in a cemetery and the head in the nearby hills. He kept the hands, from which he drank blood and ate part of them. Fearing that the police would find the corpse, he returned to the [[cemetery]] and the hills two weeks later and carried the remains back to his apartment, where he hid them in his closet.\n\n==Arrest==\nOn July 23, 1989, Miyazaki saw two sisters playing in a park in [[Hachi\u014dji]], Tokyo. He managed to separate the younger of the sisters from the older one, who stayed behind. The sisters' father arrived shortly after to find Miyazaki taking photographs of the younger daughter, who he had convinced to strip nude. The father attacked Miyazaki, but was unable to restrain him.<ref>https://www.abc.net.au/news/2008-06-18/japan-confirms-execution-of-cannibal-killer/2475810</ref><ref name=keller /> After fleeing on foot, Miyazaki eventually returned to the park to retrieve his car, whereupon he was arrested by police responding to a call by the father. A search of Miyazaki's two-room bungalow produced 5,763 videotapes, some containing [[anime]] and [[Slasher film|slasher]] films (later used as reasoning for his crimes). Interspersed among them was video footage and pictures of his victims. He was also reported to be a fan of [[horror film]]s, of which he had a collection. Miyazaki, who retained a perpetually calm and collected demeanor during his trial, appeared indifferent to his capture.<ref>{{cite news|author=Schoenberger, Karl|url=https://www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-1989-09-09-mn-1579-story.html|title=Sordid Serial-Killing Case Exposes the Other Side of Innocence in Japan|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|date=9 September 1989}}</ref>\n\n==Moral panic==\nThe [[News media|media]] called him \"The [[Otaku]] Murderer\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://scaredyet.net/the-otaku-killer-miyazaki-tsutomu/|title=The Otaku Killer: Miyazaki Tsutomu|author=Oliviera, James|date=3 January 2010|access-date=7 January 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150107074646/http://scaredyet.net/the-otaku-killer-miyazaki-tsutomu/|archive-date=7 January 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> His killings caused a [[moral panic]] against otaku, accusing anime and horror films of making him a murderer. Various newspapers claimed that Miyazaki had retreated into a fantasy world of manga as a result of his neglected upbringing.<ref name=Kinsella>{{cite journal|last=Kinsella|first=Sharon|year=1998|title=Amateur Manga Subculture and the Otaku Panic|journal=Journal of Japanese Studies|volume=24|issue=2|pages=308\u20139|url=http://www.kinsellaresearch.com/new/Japanese%20Subculture.pdf|publisher=Washington University Press}}</ref> Keigo Okonogi, a [[psychoanalyst]] at [[Tokyo International University]], told the ''Sh\u016bkan Post'' that:\n\n{{quote |text=\nThe danger of a whole generation of youth who do not even experience the most primary two- or three-way relationship between themselves and their mother and father, and who cannot make the transition from a fantasy world of videos and manga to reality, is now extreme.<ref name=Kinsella/>\n}}\n\nThese reports were disputed. In [[Eiji \u014ctsuka]]'s book on the crime, he argued that Miyazaki's collection of pornography was probably added or amended by a photographer in order to highlight his perversity.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www1.odn.ne.jp/kamiya-ta/gisi.html|script-title=ja:\u5927\u585a\u82f1\u5fd7\u300e\u300c\u304a\u305f\u304f\u300d\u306e\u7cbe\u795e\u53f2\u300f\uff5e\u307c\u304f\u304c\u4e2d\u5b66\u6642\u4ee3\u306b\u3064\u304f\u3063\u305f\u300c\u507d\u53f2\u300d\u306b\u3064\u3044\u3066|trans-title=Hideshi Otsuka \"Psychical History of Otaku\"-\"About the \"fake history\" I made during junior high school\"|language=ja|author=Kousetsu Kamiya|access-date=9 May 2019}}</ref> Another critic, Fumiya Ichihashi, suspected the released information was playing up to public stereotypes and fears about otaku, as the police knew they would help cement a conviction.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sunfield.ne.jp/~mike/books/nonfiction/crime/author/ichihashi_fumiya/miyazaki.htm|title=Miyazaki Tsutomu Jiken|publisher=Japanese Literature Webring|access-date=9 May 2019}}</ref> Sharon Kinsella asserts that large collections of manga and videos were typical in the rooms of youths living in the Tokyo area at the time.<ref name=Kinsella/>\n\n==Trial and execution==\nThe trial began on March 30, 1990. Often talking nonsensically, Miyazaki blamed his actions on \"Rat Man\", an [[alter ego]] who Miyazaki claimed forced him to kill; he spent time during the trial drawing \"Rat Man\" in cartoon form.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/world/asia/article4156285.ece|title=Japanese 'cannibal killer' executed in Tokyo |work=[[The Times]]|date=17 June 2008|access-date=17 June 2008|location=London|author=Lewis, Leo|archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/60qqMCSKQ?url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/world/asia/article4156285.ece |archive-date=11 August 2011|url-status=live}}</ref> Miyazaki's father refused to pay for his son's legal defense and committed suicide in 1994.<ref name=abc/> \n\nThe seven-year trial focused on Miyazaki's mental state at the time of the murders. Under Japanese law, people of unsound minds are not subject to punishment, and the feeble-minded are entitled to reduced sentences. Three teams of court-appointed expert psychiatrists came to differing conclusions about Miyazaki's ability to tell right from wrong. Two teams determined him to be feeble-minded\u2014one team concluding that he was [[schizophrenia|schizophrenic]], the other that he had [[multiple personality disorder]]. A third team found that although Miyazaki had a personality disorder, he was still capable of taking responsibility for his actions.<ref name=\"JapanTimes1997-04-14\">{{cite news |title=Serial child-killer Miyazaki gets death sentence |url=https://www.japantimes.co.jp/news/1997/04/14/national/serial-child-killer-miyazaki-gets-death-sentence/ |access-date=27 June 2019 |work=[[The Japan Times]] |date=14 April 1997}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Tokyo District Court]] judged him aware of the magnitude and consequences of his crimes and therefore accountable. He was sentenced to death on April 14, 1997.<ref name=\"JapanTimes1997-04-14\"/> His death sentence was upheld by both the [[Tokyo High Court]], on June 28, 2001, and the [[Supreme Court of Japan|Supreme Court of Justice]] on January 17, 2006.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://english.people.com.cn/200601/17/eng20060117_236139.html|title=Japan's Supreme Court upholds death penalty on child killer|work=[[People's Daily]]|location=Beijing|agency=[[Xinhua]]|date=17 January 2006|access-date=9 May 2019}}</ref>\n\nHe described his serial murders as an \"act of benevolence\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://jmjp.jp/topics/2008/06/post_492.html|script-title=ja:\u7570\u5e38\u306a\u72af\u7f6a\u3001\u907a\u65cf\u3078\u306e\u8b1d\u7f6a\u3082\u306a\u304f\u2026\u5bae\u5d0e\u6b7b\u5211\u56da|language=ja|location=Tokyo|date=17 June 2008|access-date=9 May 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/asia/japan/2144503/Nerd-cult-murderer-executed.html|title=Nerd cult murderer executed|work=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|date=17 June 2008|access-date=8 May 2019|location=London|author=Ryall, Julian}}</ref> Child killer [[Kaoru Kobayashi (murderer)|Kaoru Kobayashi]] described himself as \"the next Tsutomu Miyazaki or [[Mamoru Takuma]]\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.japantimes.co.jp/news/2005/04/19/national/defendant-admits-abducting-and-killing-schoolgirl-in-nara/|title=Defendant admits abducting and killing schoolgirl in Nara|work=[[The Japan Times]]|agency=[[Kyodo News]] |access-date=9 May 2019|date=19 April 2005}}</ref> Miyazaki stated, \"I won't allow him to call himself 'the second Tsutomu Miyazaki' when he hasn't even undergone a psychiatric examination.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.yomiuri.co.jp/dy/national/20080618TDY02306.htm|title=Miyazaki unrepentant to the last / Serial child killer goes to execution without apologizing or explaining his thinking|work=[[Yomiuri Shimbun]]|location=Tokyo|date=18 June 2008|access-date=18 June 2008|archive-url=https://archive.is/20080621044230/http://www.yomiuri.co.jp/dy/national/20080618TDY02306.htm|archive-date=21 June 2008}}</ref>\n\n[[Minister of Justice (Japan)|Minister of Justice]] [[Kunio Hatoyama]] signed his death warrant and Miyazaki was hanged on June 17, 2008.<ref>{{cite news|author=Yamaguchi, Mari|url=https://www.chron.com/news/nation-world/article/Japan-executes-3-including-serial-killer-of-1767054.php|title=Japan executes 3, including serial killer who mutilated young girls|work=[[Houston Chronicle]]|agency=[[Associated Press]]|date=2008-06-17|location=Neuilly-sur-Seine, France|access-date=9 May 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2008/06/17/AR2008061701131.html|title=Japan Hangs Three Killers As Pace of Executions Rises|work=[[The Washington Post]]|date=2008-06-17|access-date=9 May 2019|author=Harden, Blaine}}</ref> The unusual swiftness of his execution as well as its timing soon after the [[Akihabara massacre]] prompted questions regarding the two incidents;<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/06/17/world/asia/17iht-japan.2.13771425.html|title=Japan Hangs Three Convicted Murderers|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=17 June 2008|access-date=9 May 2019|author=Foster, Martin}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nikkansports.com/general/news/p-gn-tp0-20080618-373365.html|script-title=ja:\u7121\u5dee\u5225\u6bba\u4eba\u3078\u306e\u6291\u6b62\u52b9\u679c\uff1f\u5bae\u5d0e\u52e4\u6b7b\u5211\u57f7\u884c |language=Japanese|work=[[Nikkan Sports]]|location=Tokyo|date=18 June 2008|access-date=18 June 2008}}</ref> the [[Ministry of Justice (Japan)|Ministry of Justice]] had no comment.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.j-cast.com/2008/06/17021964.html|script-title=ja:\u5bae\u5d0e\u6b7b\u5211\u56da\u306b\u300c\u30b9\u30d4\u30fc\u30c9\u300d\u6b7b\u5211\u57f7\u884c\u3000\u56c1\u304b\u308c\u308b\u300c\u79cb\u8449\u539f\u4e8b\u4ef6\u300d\u306e\u5f71\u97ff\uff1f|language=ja|publisher=J-CAST|date=17 June 2008|access-date=9 May 2019}}</ref> [[Ry\u016bz\u014d Saki]] said, \"His trial was long\" and that he was \"not willing to criticize Hatoyama\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nikkansports.com/general/news/p-gn-tp0-20080618-373366.html|script-title=ja:\u4f5c\u5bb6\u4f50\u6728\u9686\u4e09\u3055\u3093\u300c\u9577\u3044\u88c1\u5224\u3060\u3063\u305f\u300d|language=ja|work=[[Nikkan Sports]]|location=Tokyo|date=18 June 2008|access-date=18 June 2008|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080619110206/http://www.nikkansports.com/general/news/p-gn-tp0-20080618-373366.html|archive-date=19 June 2008}}</ref>\n\n==Victims==\n#{{nihongo|'''Mari Konno'''|\u4eca\u91ce\u771f\u7406|''Konno Mari''}}: Four years old\n#{{nihongo|'''Masami Yoshizawa'''|\u5409\u6ca2\u6b63\u7f8e|''Yoshizawa Masami''}}: Seven years old\n#{{nihongo|'''Erika Namba'''|\u96e3\u6ce2\u7d75\u68a8\u9999|''Namba Erika''}}: Four years old\n#{{nihongo|'''Ayako Nomoto'''|\u91ce\u672c\u7dbe\u5b50|''Nomoto Ayako''}}: Five years old\n\n==See also==\n*[[Kaoru Kobayashi (murderer)|Kaoru Kobayashi]]\n*[[Insanity defense]]\n*[[Capital punishment in Japan]]\n*[[List of serial killers by country]]\n*[[John Wayne Gacy]]\n*[[Westley Allen Dodd]]\n*[[Richard Ramirez]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Miyazaki, Tsutomu}}\n[[Category:1962 births]]\n[[Category:2008 deaths]]\n[[Category:21st-century executions by Japan]]\n[[Category:Executed Japanese serial killers]]\n[[Category:Japanese cannibals]]\n[[Category:Japanese murderers of children]]\n[[Category:Japanese people convicted of child sexual abuse]]\n[[Category:Japanese people convicted of murder]]\n[[Category:Japanese people with disabilities]]\n[[Category:Male serial killers]]\n[[Category:Murder in 1988]]\n[[Category:Necrophiles]]\n[[Category:Otaku]]\n[[Category:People convicted of murder by Japan]]\n[[Category:People with personality disorders]]\n[[Category:People executed by Japan by hanging]]\n[[Category:People with dissociative identity disorder]]\n[[Category:People from Western Tokyo]]\n[[Category:People with schizophrenia]]\n[[Category:Vampirism (crime)]]\n", "name_user": "86.145.222.107", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tsutomu_Miyazaki"}
{"title_page": "Bandana (pop band)", "text_new": "{{Infobox musical artist\n| name = Bandana\n| image = Recital.jpg\n| caption = Bandana performing in Buenos Aires\n| background = group_or_band\n| origin = [[Buenos Aires, Argentina]]\n| genre = {{Flatlist|*[[Pop music|Pop]]\n*[[dance-pop]]\n*[[teen pop]]}}\n| years_active = 2001&ndash;2004<br/>2016&ndash;present\n| label = [[Sony BMG]] (2001&ndash;04) <br /> [[Sony Music Entertainment]] (2016&ndash;present)\n| associated_acts =[[Mambr\u00fa]], [[Wisin]]\n| current_members =[[Lourdes Cecilia Fern\u00e1ndez]] <br /> [[Valeria Gastaldi]] <br />[[Mar\u00eda Elizabeth Vera]]\n| past_members =[[Ivonne Guzm\u00e1n]] <br/>[[Virginia Da Cunha]]}}\n'''Bandana''' is an Argentine pop [[girl group]] formed in 2001. Following the international trend of [[teen pop]] girl groups established by the [[Spice Girls]], the five members of Bandana \u2014 [[Ivonne Guzm\u00e1n]], [[Lourdes Cecilia Fern\u00e1ndez]], [[Valeria Gastaldi]], [[Virginia Da Cunha]] and [[Mar\u00eda Elizabeth Vera]] \u2014 were selected on the TV show ''[[Popstars]]'' and were a carefully marketed product that became a phenomenon in the country, particularly among young girls.\n\n==History==\nTheir self-titled debut album was released in 2001 on [[Sony BMG|Sony BMG Records]], led by the hit single \"Guapas\", and was certified four-times [[Platinum record|platinum]] by the [[CAPIF]].<ref name=\"billboard\">{{cite magazine |last=Fern\u00e1ndez Bitar|first=Marcelo|date=16 August 2003|title=Bandana Launches Multimedia Assault With Third Set|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=OREEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA25|magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|publisher=Nielsen Business Media, Inc.|access-date=30 May 2016|issn=0006-2510|volume=115|number=33}}</ref> Despite being initially snubbed by many critics and artists, Bandana emerged as Argentina's best-selling act since 2001.<ref name=\"billboard\"/>\n\nAt the time of their disbandment in 2004, the combined sales of Bandana's three studio albums were estimated to be 450,000 copies sold.<ref name=\"separacion\">{{cite web |url=http://www.lanacion.com.ar/573231-se-separan-las-bandana|title=Se separan las Bandana|date=15 February 2004|work=[[La Naci\u00f3n]]|publisher=La Naci\u00f3n SA|access-date=30 May 2016|language=Spanish}}</ref> Their career was marked by several landmarks for Argentine musicians \u2014 specially bearing in mind the [[1998\u20132002 Argentine great depression]]:<ref name=\"billboard\"/> 280 thousand tickets were sold to see them perform in the [[Teatro Gran Rex]] (with a total of 86 concerts in the venue); they performed twice for a total of 90 thousand people in the [[Jos\u00e9 Amalfitani Stadium|V\u00e9lez S\u00e1rsfield Stadium]]; and released ''Vivir intentando'', a film starring themselves that was seen by over 1 million people.<ref name=\"separacion\"/>\n\nIn 2016, Bandana announced a reunion concert (without Ivonne Guzm\u00e1n) at the Lola Membrives Theatre in Buenos Aires; due to the high demand for tickets, the group has added five more dates.<ref name=\"tn\">{{cite web |url=http://tn.com.ar/musica/hoy/bandana-subio-al-escenario-para-anunciar-su-regreso_676916|title=Bandana volvi\u00f3 al escenario|language=Spanish |date=30 May 2016|publisher=[[Todo Noticias|TN]]. [[Clar\u00edn Group]]|access-date=20 May 2016}}</ref> The concerts sold out within an hour and a half.<ref name=\"tn\"/> The band also released a new album, titled ''La Vuelta'' which contains new versions of some of their biggest hits. On January 16, 2017, the band released their first original song ever since 2003 entitled \"Bomb\u00f3n\". The following day, da Cunha announced her departure from the band. In March, 2017 the 3 Bandana members, Lourdes, Valeria and Lisa, flew to the US to record the music video for  their first single since their comeback, \"Bomb\u00f3n\" featuring Wisin. The music video was produced and directed by Lourival Rodriguez and co-directed by Ruslan Shakirov. It was shot in a Mansion in Miami Beach, FL.\n\nFollowing da Cunha's departure, the band continues to release new singles, including \"No No No\" and \"Baila\" in 2018, and their latest single, \"En la Punta de la Lengua\" in February 2019.\n\n==Members==\n\nThe original group consisted of 5 girls:\n\n* [[Ivonne Guzm\u00e1n]] <small>(2001\u201404)</small>\n* [[Lourdes Cecilia Fern\u00e1ndez]] <small>(2001\u201404, 2016\u2014present)</small>\n* [[Valeria Gastaldi]] <small>(2001\u201404, 2016\u2014present)</small>\n* [[Virginia Da Cunha]] <small>(2001\u201404, 2016\u201417)</small>\n* [[Mar\u00eda Elizabeth Vera]] <small>(2001\u201404, 2016\u2014present)</small>\n\nAll the girls hailed from [[Buenos Aires]], apart from Guzm\u00e1n, who is a native of [[Colombia]].\n\nUpon the band's comeback tour in 2016, Guzm\u00e1n decided not to return, being the only member who did not rejoin. Guzm\u00e1n's role was not replaced.\n\nOn January 17, 2017, da Cunha revealed through her Instagram account she had left the band to focus on her solo career. The rest of the members announced subsequently that they would not replace da Cunha and instead, would continue as a 3-girl group.\n\n==Casting==\n\nFormed in 2001 on the reality TV show [[Popstars]], 5 girls were selected from 5,000's of contestants who had attended the casting.  Their emergence coincided with a period of [[Argentine economic crisis (1999-2002)|nationwide economic depression]].  As such, their success contrasted greatly with the general mood of the country, & one of the judges commented that \"this was an opportunity to shine at a very downbeat moment for Argentina\".<ref name=\"pagina12.com.ar\">[http://www.pagina12.com.ar/2001/01-11/01-11-14/pag29.htm \"El sue\u00f1o del estrellato veloz convertido en realidad\"] P\u00e1gina 12 Article Juli\u00e1n Gorodischer 01-11-2001</ref>  The final line-up was unusual in the sense that the girls didn't conform to traditional ideas of beauty: Ivonne wore braces & Lourdes was known as ''la peti'' (''shorty'') due to her height.  Judge Afo Verde noted that ''\"appearance didn't matter to us, what each girl conveyed was most important\"''.<ref name=\"pagina12.com.ar\"/>\n\n== Musical history ==\n\nTheir first self-titled album, ''Bandana'', was the best-selling album of 2001 in Argentina, turning platinum soon after release and achieving 4 platinum certifications.<ref>[http://www.music.com/group/bandana/2/biography/ Biography] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070926224728/http://www.music.com/group/bandana/2/biography/ |date=2007-09-26 }} Music.com, Drago Bonacich 18-06-2004</ref>  It spawned a number of hits including ''C\u00f3mo Puede Ser'', ''Guapas'' & ''Maldita Noche''.  They also completed a successful tour, selling out [[Buenos Aires]]' biggest theatre, [[Teatro Gran Rex]], more than 40 times during winter vacations (July).\n<!-- Deleted image removed: [[Image:Bandana - Pelicula.jpg|thumb|right|200px|''Vivir Intentando - The Movie'' (2003)]] -->\nLater in 2002, they recorded a Spanish version of [[Can't Help Falling in Love]] by Elvis Presley ''(Muero De Amor Por T\u00ed)'', for the [[Disney]] film [[Lilo & Stitch]] .  In 2002, they released their second album, ''Noche'' (''Night''), which wasn't as successful as the first but it was still the best-selling album of 2002 in Argentina.<ref>http://www.portalcomunicacion.com/both/opc/argentina2003.pd{{Dead link|date=June 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> In 2003, they released their third studio album, titled ''Vivir Intentando'' which was also the soundtrack of their film of the same name released during the same year. They also won '''Best New Artist\u2014Southeast''' at the [[MTV Video Music Awards Latin America]].<ref name=\"mtvla.com\">[http://www.mtvla.com/canal/especiales/vmala/02/nominados/artistanuevosureste.jhtml?i=4 Best New Artist Southeast \u2013 Winners] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070927004318/http://www.mtvla.com/canal/especiales/vmala/02/nominados/artistanuevosureste.jhtml?i=4 |date=2007-09-27 }}, MTVLA.com \u2014 MTV Video Music Awards Latinoam\u00e9rica</ref>  In December 2002, they performed a joint concert with [[Mambr\u00fa]] in the [[Estadio Jos\u00e9 Amalfitani|V\u00e9lez S\u00e1rsfield]] stadium with over 40,000 tickets sold.\n\nIn order to promote themselves internationally, they traveled to the USA, appearing in [[New York City|New York]] & [[Miami]]<ref>[http://www.music.com/group/bandana/2/biography/ Biography] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070926224728/http://www.music.com/group/bandana/2/biography/ |date=2007-09-26 }}, Music.com, Drago Bonacich 18-06-2004</</ref> & also featuring on the cover of [[Billboard Magazine]].  This was notable for being the first time that an Argentine group had achieved this feat.<ref>[http://www.terra.com.ar/canales/musica/75/75217.html '\u00a1Las chicas en la tapa de Billboard!'], Article, Terra.com.ar 15-08-2003</ref>\n\nIn 2016 they are back in order to do several shows and a tour around the country. They revealed through interviews that reuniting had always been a possibility, but it kept being postponed due to some of the members' pregnancies and other professional commitments. A new album, ''La Vuelta'' was released to celebrate their reunion, which contains revised versions of some of their biggest hits. The track list is also the set list of their tour.\n\nOn January 16, 2017, the group released their first original song since 2003 entitled \"Bomb\u00f3n\" featuring Puerto Rican rapper [[Wisin]]. The following day, da Cunha revealed she had left the band, hence why she did not participate in the recording of this song. This brand new song serves as the main theme of one of [[Telef\u00e9]]'s reality show, ''Despedida de Soltero'' (''Stag Party'').\n\n== Cultural Impact ==\nFollowing on from a trend established by the [[Spice Girls]] in the UK & internationally in the late 1990s, Bandana became a carefully marketed product which was especially popular among young girls.  Many licensed products with their brand were available to purchase, and contributed to the heightened interest in the group, occasionally referred to as 'Bandanamania'.<ref name=\"Biography\">[http://www.mtvla.com/bands/az/bandana/bio.jhtml Biography] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070927004337/http://www.mtvla.com/bands/az/bandana/bio.jhtml |date=2007-09-27 }} MTVLA.com</ref>  Their signature [[bandanas]] of varying colours were quickly imitated by the teen population, as were their lyrics & dance routines.<ref name=\"Biography\"/>\n\nFrom 2001 to 2003, there was an official ''Bandana'' store selling lots of merchandisings. The store was located at Avenida Corrientes, right besides Teatro Gran Rex.\n\n== Vivir Intentando (Go For It) ==\nIn 2003 they released their first movie, '''[[Vivir Intentando]]''', filmed on location in [[Buenos Aires]]. It premiered in Argentina on 14 June 2003,<ref>[https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0346571/releaseinfo IMDB] Release Dates</ref> & met with mixed reviews.  One critic claimed it a success \"''thanks to the competent technical aspects, precise use of emotion that plays with the audience, but above all, the atmosphere which it creates in the cinema''\".<ref>[http://www.zonafreak.com.ar/pantallag/vivir_intentando.htm 'El espect\u00e1culo del a\u00f1o'] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070927213745/http://www.zonafreak.com.ar/pantallag/vivir_intentando.htm |date=2007-09-27 }}, Review - Zonafreak.com.ar, Ygnacio Cervio</ref>  Others were less complimentary, commenting ''\"their acting talents are just passable.....the songs shine due to the absence thereof.....& the script comes straight from the 'teenager dreams of being a singer' handbook\"''.<ref>[http://www.clarin.com/diario/2003/06/26/c-00701.htm  'Una oportunidad fallida'] Clarin.com, Review - Diego Lerer 26-06-2003</ref>  In spite of this, the movie grossed over ARS 10,500,000.<ref>[https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0346571/business IMDB] Box Office/Business</ref> and had a bigger B.O. than many international blockbusters.\n\n== Discography ==\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-3}}\n\n=== Albums ===\n* ''Bandana'' (2001)\n**'''Label:''' [[Virgin Records]], [[Jive Records]] US, [BMG] LA\n* ''Noche'' (2002)\n**'''Label:''' BMG, [[Jive Records]] US, [BMG] LA\n* ''Vivir Intentando (Go for It)'' (2003)\n**'''Label:''' BMG, [[Jive Records]] US, [BMG] LA\n* ''Hasta Siempre'' (2004) - ''Live Hits album''\n**'''Label:''' [[Jive Records]] US, [[Sony BMG Music Entertainment]] AR\n* ''La Vuelta'' (2016) - ''Remix album''\n**'''Label:''' [[Sony Music Entertainment]] AR\n\n{{col-3}}\n\n===DVDs===\n* ''[[Vivir Intentando]]'' (2003)\n* ''Hasta Siempre'' (2004) - Live hits\n\n===Tours===\n* ''Gira Argentina'' (2002&ndash;2003)\n* ''Gira Espa\u00f1a y Latin America''' (2003&ndash;2004)\n* ''Gira Argentina: Hasta Siempre'' (2004)\n* ''Bandana: La Vuelta'' (2016)\n\n{{col-3}}\n\n===Singles===\n* 2001: \"Guapas\"\n* 2002: \"C\u00f3mo Puede Ser\"\n* 2002: \"Maldita Noche\"\n* 2002: \"Doce Horas\"\n* 2002: \"Muero de Amor Por Ti\" (for the film ''[[Lilo & Stitch]]'')\n* 2002: \"Llega La Noche\"\n* 2002: \"Un Demonio\"\n* 2003: \"Necesito Tu Amor\"\n* 2003: \"Hoy Empieza\"\n* 2003: \"Sigo Dando Vueltas\"\n* 2003: \"Hasta El D\u00eda de Hoy\"\n* 2004: \"\u00bfQu\u00e9 Pasa Con Vos?\"\n* 2004: \"A Bailar\"\n* 2004: \"Canto Con Vos\"\n* 2016: \"Llega La Noche\" <small>(2016 version)</small>\n* 2017: \"Bomb\u00f3n\" (feat. [[Wisin]])\n* 2018: \"No No No\"\n* 2018: \"Baila\"\n* 2019: \"En la Punta de la Lengua\"\n\n{{s-end}}\n\n== Awards and nominations ==\n* [[MTV Video Music Awards Latin America]]\n** 2002: Best New Artist \u2013 '''WON'''<ref name=\"mtvla.com\"/>\n* [[CAPIF|Premios CAPIF]]:\n**2002: Best Pop Band \u2013 '''Nominated'''<ref>[http://www.capif.org.ar/PremiosGardel.asp?CodOp=GAQV&CO=8 CAPIF Official]</ref>\n**2002: Best New Artist \u2013 '''Nominated'''<ref name=\"CAPIF Oficial\">[http://www.capif.org.ar/PremiosGardel.asp?CodOp=GAQV&CO=8 CAPIF Oficial]</ref>\n**2002: Best Music Publishing \u2013 '''Nominated'''<ref name=\"CAPIF Oficial\"/>\n**2003: Best Pop Album \u2013 '''Nominated'''<ref name=\"CAPIF Oficial\"/>\n**2004: Best Pop Album \u2013 '''Nominated'''<ref name=\"CAPIF Oficial\"/>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[List of all-female bands]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n[https://beginnersfashion.com/how-to-tie-a-bandana-headband/ how to tie a bandana headband]\n\n==External links==\n{{Commonscat|Bandana (musical group)}}\u200e\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20080116083410/http://www.guapasxsiempre.ar.nu/ Official Website ''En Espa\u00f1ol'']\n*{{IMDb title|id=0346571|title=Vivir Intentando}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20070313233053/http://www.emimusica.com.ar/comunicacion/lourdes_televisivamente/index-flash.html Lourdes Fern\u00e1ndez's webpage at EMI Argentina]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20080822121212/http://www.lourdesweb.com.ar/index-flash.html Lourdes Fern\u00e1ndez's Official Site]\n*[http://www.viriweb.com/ Virginia Da Cunha's Personal Site]\n*[http://www.valeriagastaldi.net/ Valeria Gastaldi's Official Site]\n*[http://www.generacionvg.com.ar/ Valeria Gastaldi's Fans Club Site]{{Dead link|date=June 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bandana}}\n[[Category:Argentine pop music groups]]\n[[Category:Argentine girl groups]]\n[[Category:Latin music groups]]\n[[Category:Musical groups established in 2001]]\n[[Category:Popstars winners]]\n[[Category:2001 establishments in Argentina]]\n[[Category:Musical groups from Buenos Aires]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox musical artist\n| name = Bandana\n| image = Recital.jpg\n| caption = Bandana performing in Buenos Aires\n| background = group_or_band\n| origin = [[Buenos Aires, Argentina]]\n| genre = {{Flatlist|*[[Pop music|Pop]]\n*[[dance-pop]]\n*[[teen pop]]}}\n| years_active = 2001&ndash;2004<br/>2016&ndash;present\n| label = [[Sony BMG]] (2001&ndash;04) <br /> [[Sony Music Entertainment]] (2016&ndash;present)\n| associated_acts =[[Mambr\u00fa]], [[Wisin]]\n| current_members =[[Lourdes Cecilia Fern\u00e1ndez]] <br /> [[Valeria Gastaldi]] <br />[[Mar\u00eda Elizabeth Vera]]\n| past_members =[[Ivonne Guzm\u00e1n]] <br/>[[Virginia Da Cunha]]}}\n'''Bandana''' is an Argentine pop [[girl group]] formed in 2001. Following the international trend of [[teen pop]] girl groups established by the [[Spice Girls]], the five members of Bandana \u2014 [[Ivonne Guzm\u00e1n]], [[Lourdes Cecilia Fern\u00e1ndez]], [[Valeria Gastaldi]], [[Virginia Da Cunha]] and [[Mar\u00eda Elizabeth Vera]] \u2014 were selected on the TV show ''[[Popstars]]'' and were a carefully marketed product that became a phenomenon in the country, particularly among young girls.\n\n==History==\nTheir self-titled debut album was released in 2001 on [[Sony BMG|Sony BMG Records]], led by the hit single \"Guapas\", and was certified four-times [[Platinum record|platinum]] by the [[CAPIF]].<ref name=\"billboard\">{{cite magazine |last=Fern\u00e1ndez Bitar|first=Marcelo|date=16 August 2003|title=Bandana Launches Multimedia Assault With Third Set|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=OREEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA25|magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|publisher=Nielsen Business Media, Inc.|access-date=30 May 2016|issn=0006-2510|volume=115|number=33}}</ref> Despite being initially snubbed by many critics and artists, Bandana emerged as Argentina's best-selling act since 2001.<ref name=\"billboard\"/>\n\nAt the time of their disbandment in 2004, the combined sales of Bandana's three studio albums were estimated to be 450,000 copies sold.<ref name=\"separacion\">{{cite web |url=http://www.lanacion.com.ar/573231-se-separan-las-bandana|title=Se separan las Bandana|date=15 February 2004|work=[[La Naci\u00f3n]]|publisher=La Naci\u00f3n SA|access-date=30 May 2016|language=Spanish}}</ref> Their career was marked by several landmarks for Argentine musicians \u2014 specially bearing in mind the [[1998\u20132002 Argentine great depression]]:<ref name=\"billboard\"/> 280 thousand tickets were sold to see them perform in the [[Teatro Gran Rex]] (with a total of 86 concerts in the venue); they performed twice for a total of 90 thousand people in the [[Jos\u00e9 Amalfitani Stadium|V\u00e9lez S\u00e1rsfield Stadium]]; and released ''Vivir intentando'', a film starring themselves that was seen by over 1 million people.<ref name=\"separacion\"/>\n\nIn 2016, Bandana announced a reunion concert (without Ivonne Guzm\u00e1n) at the Lola Membrives Theatre in Buenos Aires; due to the high demand for tickets, the group has added five more dates.<ref name=\"tn\">{{cite web |url=http://tn.com.ar/musica/hoy/bandana-subio-al-escenario-para-anunciar-su-regreso_676916|title=Bandana volvi\u00f3 al escenario|language=Spanish |date=30 May 2016|publisher=[[Todo Noticias|TN]]. [[Clar\u00edn Group]]|access-date=20 May 2016}}</ref> The concerts sold out within an hour and a half.<ref name=\"tn\"/> The band also released a new album, titled ''La Vuelta'' which contains new versions of some of their biggest hits. On January 16, 2017, the band released their first original song ever since 2003 entitled \"Bomb\u00f3n\". The following day, da Cunha announced her departure from the band. In March, 2017 the 3 Bandana members, Lourdes, Valeria and Lisa, flew to the US to record the music video for  their first single since their comeback, \"Bomb\u00f3n\" featuring Wisin. The music video was produced and directed by Lourival Rodriguez and co-directed by Ruslan Shakirov. It was shot in a Mansion in Miami Beach, FL.\n\nFollowing da Cunha's departure, the band continues to release new singles, including \"No No No\" and \"Baila\" in 2018, and their latest single, \"En la Punta de la Lengua\" in February 2019.\n\n==Members==\n\nThe original group consisted of 5 girls:\n\n* [[Ivonne Guzm\u00e1n]] <small>(2001\u201404)</small>\n* [[Lourdes Cecilia Fern\u00e1ndez]] <small>(2001\u201404, 2016\u2014present)</small>\n* [[Valeria Gastaldi]] <small>(2001\u201404, 2016\u2014present)</small>\n* [[Virginia Da Cunha]] <small>(2001\u201404, 2016\u201417)</small>\n* [[Mar\u00eda Elizabeth Vera]] <small>(2001\u201404, 2016\u2014present)</small>\n\nAll the girls hailed from [[Buenos Aires]], apart from Guzm\u00e1n, who is a native of [[Colombia]].\n\nUpon the band's comeback tour in 2016, Guzm\u00e1n decided not to return, being the only member who did not rejoin. Guzm\u00e1n's role was not replaced.\n\nOn January 17, 2017, da Cunha revealed through her Instagram account she had left the band to focus on her solo career. The rest of the members announced subsequently that they would not replace da Cunha and instead, would continue as a 3-girl group.\n\n==Casting==\n\nFormed in 2001 on the reality TV show [[Popstars]], 5 girls were selected from 5,000's of contestants who had attended the casting.  Their emergence coincided with a period of [[Argentine economic crisis (1999-2002)|nationwide economic depression]].  As such, their success contrasted greatly with the general mood of the country, & one of the judges commented that \"this was an opportunity to shine at a very downbeat moment for Argentina\".<ref name=\"pagina12.com.ar\">[http://www.pagina12.com.ar/2001/01-11/01-11-14/pag29.htm \"El sue\u00f1o del estrellato veloz convertido en realidad\"] P\u00e1gina 12 Article Juli\u00e1n Gorodischer 01-11-2001</ref>  The final line-up was unusual in the sense that the girls didn't conform to traditional ideas of beauty: Ivonne wore braces & Lourdes was known as ''la peti'' (''shorty'') due to her height.  Judge Afo Verde noted that ''\"appearance didn't matter to us, what each girl conveyed was most important\"''.<ref name=\"pagina12.com.ar\"/>\n\n== Musical history ==\n\nTheir first self-titled album, ''Bandana'', was the best-selling album of 2001 in Argentina, turning platinum soon after release and achieving 4 platinum certifications.<ref>[http://www.music.com/group/bandana/2/biography/ Biography] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070926224728/http://www.music.com/group/bandana/2/biography/ |date=2007-09-26 }} Music.com, Drago Bonacich 18-06-2004</ref>  It spawned a number of hits including ''C\u00f3mo Puede Ser'', ''Guapas'' & ''Maldita Noche''.  They also completed a successful tour, selling out [[Buenos Aires]]' biggest theatre, [[Teatro Gran Rex]], more than 40 times during winter vacations (July).\n<!-- Deleted image removed: [[Image:Bandana - Pelicula.jpg|thumb|right|200px|''Vivir Intentando - The Movie'' (2003)]] -->\nLater in 2002, they recorded a Spanish version of [[Can't Help Falling in Love]] by Elvis Presley ''(Muero De Amor Por T\u00ed)'', for the [[Disney]] film [[Lilo & Stitch]] .  In 2002, they released their second album, ''Noche'' (''Night''), which wasn't as successful as the first but it was still the best-selling album of 2002 in Argentina.<ref>http://www.portalcomunicacion.com/both/opc/argentina2003.pd{{Dead link|date=June 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> In 2003, they released their third studio album, titled ''Vivir Intentando'' which was also the soundtrack of their film of the same name released during the same year. They also won '''Best New Artist\u2014Southeast''' at the [[MTV Video Music Awards Latin America]].<ref name=\"mtvla.com\">[http://www.mtvla.com/canal/especiales/vmala/02/nominados/artistanuevosureste.jhtml?i=4 Best New Artist Southeast \u2013 Winners] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070927004318/http://www.mtvla.com/canal/especiales/vmala/02/nominados/artistanuevosureste.jhtml?i=4 |date=2007-09-27 }}, MTVLA.com \u2014 MTV Video Music Awards Latinoam\u00e9rica</ref>  In December 2002, they performed a joint concert with [[Mambr\u00fa]] in the [[Estadio Jos\u00e9 Amalfitani|V\u00e9lez S\u00e1rsfield]] stadium with over 40,000 tickets sold.\n\nIn order to promote themselves internationally, they traveled to the USA, appearing in [[New York City|New York]] & [[Miami]]<ref>[http://www.music.com/group/bandana/2/biography/ Biography] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070926224728/http://www.music.com/group/bandana/2/biography/ |date=2007-09-26 }}, Music.com, Drago Bonacich 18-06-2004</</ref> & also featuring on the cover of [[Billboard Magazine]].  This was notable for being the first time that an Argentine group had achieved this feat.<ref>[http://www.terra.com.ar/canales/musica/75/75217.html '\u00a1Las chicas en la tapa de Billboard!'], Article, Terra.com.ar 15-08-2003</ref>\n\nIn 2016 they are back in order to do several shows and a tour around the country. They revealed through interviews that reuniting had always been a possibility, but it kept being postponed due to some of the members' pregnancies and other professional commitments. A new album, ''La Vuelta'' was released to celebrate their reunion, which contains revised versions of some of their biggest hits. The track list is also the set list of their tour.\n\nOn January 16, 2017, the group released their first original song since 2003 entitled \"Bomb\u00f3n\" featuring Puerto Rican rapper [[Wisin]]. The following day, da Cunha revealed she had left the band, hence why she did not participate in the recording of this song. This brand new song serves as the main theme of one of [[Telef\u00e9]]'s reality show, ''Despedida de Soltero'' (''Stag Party'').\n\n== Cultural Impact ==\nFollowing on from a trend established by the [[Spice Girls]] in the UK & internationally in the late 1990s, Bandana became a carefully marketed product which was especially popular among young girls.  Many licensed products with their brand were available to purchase, and contributed to the heightened interest in the group, occasionally referred to as 'Bandanamania'.<ref name=\"Biography\">[http://www.mtvla.com/bands/az/bandana/bio.jhtml Biography] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070927004337/http://www.mtvla.com/bands/az/bandana/bio.jhtml |date=2007-09-27 }} MTVLA.com</ref>  Their signature [[bandanas]] of varying colours were quickly imitated by the teen population, as were their lyrics & dance routines.<ref name=\"Biography\"/>\n\nFrom 2001 to 2003, there was an official ''Bandana'' store selling lots of merchandisings. The store was located at Avenida Corrientes, right besides Teatro Gran Rex.\n\n== Vivir Intentando (Go For It) ==\nIn 2003 they released their first movie, '''[[Vivir Intentando]]''', filmed on location in [[Buenos Aires]]. It premiered in Argentina on 14 June 2003,<ref>[https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0346571/releaseinfo IMDB] Release Dates</ref> & met with mixed reviews.  One critic claimed it a success \"''thanks to the competent technical aspects, precise use of emotion that plays with the audience, but above all, the atmosphere which it creates in the cinema''\".<ref>[http://www.zonafreak.com.ar/pantallag/vivir_intentando.htm 'El espect\u00e1culo del a\u00f1o'] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070927213745/http://www.zonafreak.com.ar/pantallag/vivir_intentando.htm |date=2007-09-27 }}, Review - Zonafreak.com.ar, Ygnacio Cervio</ref>  Others were less complimentary, commenting ''\"their acting talents are just passable.....the songs shine due to the absence thereof.....& the script comes straight from the 'teenager dreams of being a singer' handbook\"''.<ref>[http://www.clarin.com/diario/2003/06/26/c-00701.htm  'Una oportunidad fallida'] Clarin.com, Review - Diego Lerer 26-06-2003</ref>  In spite of this, the movie grossed over ARS 10,500,000.<ref>[https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0346571/business IMDB] Box Office/Business</ref> and had a bigger B.O. than many international blockbusters.\n\n== Discography ==\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-3}}\n\n=== Albums ===\n* ''Bandana'' (2001)\n**'''Label:''' [[Virgin Records]], [[Jive Records]] US, [BMG] LA\n* ''Noche'' (2002)\n**'''Label:''' BMG, [[Jive Records]] US, [BMG] LA\n* ''Vivir Intentando (Go for It)'' (2003)\n**'''Label:''' BMG, [[Jive Records]] US, [BMG] LA\n* ''Hasta Siempre'' (2004) - ''Live Hits album''\n**'''Label:''' [[Jive Records]] US, [[Sony BMG Music Entertainment]] AR\n* ''La Vuelta'' (2016) - ''Remix album''\n**'''Label:''' [[Sony Music Entertainment]] AR\n\n{{col-3}}\n\n===DVDs===\n* ''[[Vivir Intentando]]'' (2003)\n* ''Hasta Siempre'' (2004) - Live hits\n\n===Tours===\n* ''Gira Argentina'' (2002&ndash;2003)\n* ''Gira Espa\u00f1a y Latin America''' (2003&ndash;2004)\n* ''Gira Argentina: Hasta Siempre'' (2004)\n* ''Bandana: La Vuelta'' (2016)\n\n{{col-3}}\n\n===Singles===\n* 2001: \"Guapas\"\n* 2002: \"C\u00f3mo Puede Ser\"\n* 2002: \"Maldita Noche\"\n* 2002: \"Doce Horas\"\n* 2002: \"Muero de Amor Por Ti\" (for the film ''[[Lilo & Stitch]]'')\n* 2002: \"Llega La Noche\"\n* 2002: \"Un Demonio\"\n* 2003: \"Necesito Tu Amor\"\n* 2003: \"Hoy Empieza\"\n* 2003: \"Sigo Dando Vueltas\"\n* 2003: \"Hasta El D\u00eda de Hoy\"\n* 2004: \"\u00bfQu\u00e9 Pasa Con Vos?\"\n* 2004: \"A Bailar\"\n* 2004: \"Canto Con Vos\"\n* 2016: \"Llega La Noche\" <small>(2016 version)</small>\n* 2017: \"Bomb\u00f3n\" (feat. [[Wisin]])\n* 2018: \"No No No\"\n* 2018: \"Baila\"\n* 2019: \"En la Punta de la Lengua\"\n\n{{s-end}}\n\n== Awards and nominations ==\n* [[MTV Video Music Awards Latin America]]\n** 2002: Best New Artist \u2013 '''WON'''<ref name=\"mtvla.com\"/>\n* [[CAPIF|Premios CAPIF]]:\n**2002: Best Pop Band \u2013 '''Nominated'''<ref>[http://www.capif.org.ar/PremiosGardel.asp?CodOp=GAQV&CO=8 CAPIF Official]</ref>\n**2002: Best New Artist \u2013 '''Nominated'''<ref name=\"CAPIF Oficial\">[http://www.capif.org.ar/PremiosGardel.asp?CodOp=GAQV&CO=8 CAPIF Oficial]</ref>\n**2002: Best Music Publishing \u2013 '''Nominated'''<ref name=\"CAPIF Oficial\"/>\n**2003: Best Pop Album \u2013 '''Nominated'''<ref name=\"CAPIF Oficial\"/>\n**2004: Best Pop Album \u2013 '''Nominated'''<ref name=\"CAPIF Oficial\"/>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[List of all-female bands]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commonscat|Bandana (musical group)}}\u200e\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20080116083410/http://www.guapasxsiempre.ar.nu/ Official Website ''En Espa\u00f1ol'']\n*{{IMDb title|id=0346571|title=Vivir Intentando}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20070313233053/http://www.emimusica.com.ar/comunicacion/lourdes_televisivamente/index-flash.html Lourdes Fern\u00e1ndez's webpage at EMI Argentina]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20080822121212/http://www.lourdesweb.com.ar/index-flash.html Lourdes Fern\u00e1ndez's Official Site]\n*[http://www.viriweb.com/ Virginia Da Cunha's Personal Site]\n*[http://www.valeriagastaldi.net/ Valeria Gastaldi's Official Site]\n*[http://www.generacionvg.com.ar/ Valeria Gastaldi's Fans Club Site]{{Dead link|date=June 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bandana}}\n[[Category:Argentine pop music groups]]\n[[Category:Argentine girl groups]]\n[[Category:Latin music groups]]\n[[Category:Musical groups established in 2001]]\n[[Category:Popstars winners]]\n[[Category:2001 establishments in Argentina]]\n[[Category:Musical groups from Buenos Aires]]\n", "name_user": "Beginners Fashion", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eReferences)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bandana_(pop_band)"}
{"title_page": "Madden NFL 2003", "text_new": "{{Short description|2002 American football simulation video game}}\n{{Infobox video game\n| title = Madden NFL 2003\n| image = Madden2003Box.jpg\n| image_size = 256px\n| caption = [[PlayStation 2]] cover art featuring [[Marshall Faulk]]\n| developer = [[EA Tiburon]]<br />[[Budcat Creations]]\n| publisher = [[EA Sports]]\n| series    = ''[[Madden NFL]]''\n| released  = {{vgrelease|NA|August 12, 2002|NA|August 13, 2002 <small>(PSX)</small>|PAL|September 27, 2002 <small>(PC, Xbox)</small>|PAL|October 4, 2002 <small>(PS2)</small>|PAL|October 11, 2002 <small>(GC)</small>}}\n| genre     = [[Sports game|Sports]]\n| modes     = [[Single-player]], [[Multiplayer video game|multiplayer]]\n| platforms = [[Game Boy Advance]]<br>[[Nintendo GameCube|GameCube]]<br>[[Microsoft Windows]]<br>[[PlayStation (console)|PlayStation]]<br>[[PlayStation 2]]<br>[[Xbox (console)|Xbox]]\n}}\n\n'''''Madden NFL 2003''''' is an [[American football]] [[simulation video game]] based on the [[National Football League|NFL]] that was developed by [[EA Tiburon]] and [[Budcat Creations]] and published by [[EA Sports]]. The 14th installment of the ''[[Madden NFL|Madden NFL series]]'', the game features former [[St. Louis Rams]] [[Running back (American football)|running back]] [[Marshall Faulk]] on the cover. This edition of ''Madden'' was the first to have [[EA Trax]], the Mini Camp mode and to feature [[John Madden]] and [[Al Michaels]] as commentators, who took over for [[Pat Summerall]]. Although it featured the expansion [[Houston Texans]] and the relocation of the [[Seattle Seahawks]] to the NFC, it was actually the second to do so (after [[Madden NFL 2002|the previous edition]] had it done in the second season of its own Franchise mode, with the Seahawks still in the AFC and no Texans team when said mode was started). The game was released on August 12, 2002 for the [[Game Boy Advance]], [[GameCube]], [[Microsoft Windows]], [[PlayStation (console)|PlayStation]], [[PlayStation 2]] and the [[Xbox (console)|Xbox]].\n\n==Roster errors==\n* [[Bruce Matthews (American football)|Bruce Matthews]] is the starting center for the [[Tennessee Titans]] despite having retired by the start of the season.\n* Retired [[quarterback]] [[Mark Rypien]] is listed as a free agent.\n* [[Ryan Leaf]] appears as a backup quarterback for the [[Seattle Seahawks]] despite retiring before the start of training camp.\n* [[LaVar Arrington]] does not appear in the game due to him not represented by the NFL players association at the time therefore preventing him from appearing in the game, however his name can be added.\n* [[Pat Tillman]] appears as a free agent despite retiring before the season to join the military.\n* [[Tony Boselli]] appears as a left tackle for the [[Houston Texans]], however he retired before the 2002 NFL season because of injuries.\n\n==Soundtrack==\n''Madden NFL 2003'' was the first [[EA Sports]] video game to feature [[EA Trax]].\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size:90%; text-align:center; width:50%; margin: 5px;\"\n|-\n!colspan=\"2\" style=\"background:#C8C8FF;\" | Madden NFL 2003 Soundtrack\n|-\n!style=\"background:#ddddee;\" | Artist\n!style=\"background:#ddddee;\" | Song\n|-\n|[[Andrew W.K.]]\n|\"[[Party Hard]]\"\n|-\n|[[Audiovent]]\n|\"[[The Energy]]\"\n|-\n|[[Dry Cell (band)|Dry Cell]]\n|\"Body Crumbles\"\n|-\n|[[Epidemic (band)|Epidemic]]\n|\"Walk Away\"\n|-\n|[[Good Charlotte]]\n|\"[[The Anthem (Good Charlotte song)|The Anthem]]\"\n|-\n|[[Hed PE]]\n|\"Suck It Up\"\n|-\n|[[Bon Jovi]]\n|\"[[Everyday (Bon Jovi song)|Everyday]]\"\n|-\n|[[Nappy Roots]]\n|\"[[Awnaw]]\" (Rock Remix ft. [[Marcos Curiel]] of [[P.O.D.]])\n|-\n|[[OK Go]]\n|\"[[Get Over It (OK Go song)|Get Over It]]\"\n|-\n|[[Quarashi]]\n|\"[[Mr. Jinx (song)|Mr. Jinx]]\"\n|-\n|[[Seether]]\n|\"[[Fine Again]]\"\n|}\n\n==Reception==\n{{Video game reviews\n| GBA = true\n| NGC = true\n| PC = true\n| PS = true\n| PS2 = true\n| XBOX = true\n| na = true\n| All